# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] The **1866 great fire of Portland** was a large fire that spread throughout the city of Portland, Maine, on July 4, 1866—the second Independence Day after the end of the American Civil War.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] The fire burned out the morning of July 5; while over a thousand buildings were destroyed, there were few fatalities.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] Occurring five years before the Great Chicago Fire, it was the greatest fire yet seen in an American city.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] The fire started in a boat house near today's Hobson's Wharf on Commercial Street, likely caused by a firecracker or a cigar ash.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] The fire spread to a lumber yard and on to a sugar house, then spread across the city, eventually burning out early the next morning on Munjoy Hill in the city's east end.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] Four people died in the fire and 10,000 people were made homeless.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] Around 1,800 buildings (1,200 homes) were burned to the ground, including the first of three city halls which have stood at the present Congress Street location.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] Also lost was the federal Exchange Building, which was replaced with the custom house.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] Soon after the fire, Portland native and acclaimed poet Henry Wadsworth Longfellow described his old home town: "Desolation, desolation, desolation.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] It reminded me of Pompeii, that 'sepult city.'" More than 600 buildings were constructed in the four months following the fire.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The **American Civil War** (April 12, 1861 – May 26, 1865; also known by other names) was a civil war in the United States between the Union ("the North") and the Confederacy ("the South"), which was formed in 1861 by states that had seceded from the Union to preserve slavery in the United States.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The South saw slavery as threatened because of the election of Abraham Lincoln and the growing abolitionist movement in the North.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The war ended with Union victory, the dissolution of the Confederacy and the abolition of slavery, freeing four million African Americans.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Decades of controversy over slavery came to a head when Abraham Lincoln, a Republican who opposed slavery's expansion, won the 1860 presidential election.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Seven slave states in the South responded to Lincoln's victory by seceding from the United States and forming the Confederate States of America.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy seized US forts and other federal assets in the South.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The war began on April 12, 1861, when the Confederacy bombarded Fort Sumter in South Carolina.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] A wave of enthusiasm for war swept over the North and South, as military recruitment soared.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Four more Southern states seceded after the war began and, led by its president, Jefferson Davis, the Confederacy comprised eleven states, containing a third of the US population.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Four years of intense combat, mostly in the South, ensued.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] During 1861–1862 in the western theater, the Union made permanent gains, though in the eastern theater the conflict was inconclusive.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The abolition of slavery became a Union war goal on January 1, 1863, when Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which declared all slaves in rebel states to be free, applying to more than 3.5 million of the 4 million enslaved people in the country.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] To the west, the Union first destroyed the Confederacy's river navy by the summer of 1862, then much of its western armies, and seized New Orleans.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The successful 1863 Union siege of Vicksburg split the Confederacy in two at the Mississippi River, while Confederate general Robert E.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Lee's incursion north failed at the Battle of Gettysburg.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Grant's western successes led Lincoln to promote him to command of all Union armies in 1864.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Inflicting an ever-tightening naval blockade of Confederate ports, the Union marshaled resources and manpower to attack the Confederacy from all directions.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] This led to the fall of Atlanta in 1864 to Union general William Tecumseh Sherman, followed by his March to the Sea, which culminated in his taking Savannah.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The last significant battles raged around the ten-month Siege of Petersburg, gateway to the Confederate capital of Richmond.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederates abandoned Richmond, and on April 9, 1865, Lee surrendered to Grant following the Battle of Appomattox Court House, setting in motion the end of the war.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln lived to see this victory but was shot by an assassin on April 14, dying the next day.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] By the end of the war, much of the South's infrastructure had been destroyed.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy collapsed, the Thirteenth Amendment abolished slavery, and four million enslaved black people were freed.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The war-torn nation then entered the Reconstruction era in an attempt to rebuild the country, bring the former Confederate states back into the United States, and grant civil rights to freed slaves.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The war is one of the most extensively studied and written about episodes in the history of the United States.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] It remains the subject of cultural and historiographical debate.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Of continuing interest is the myth of the Lost Cause of the Confederacy.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The war was among the first to use industrial warfare.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Railroads, the electrical telegraph, steamships, the ironclad warship, and mass-produced weapons were widely used.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The war left an estimated 700,000 soldiers dead, along with an undetermined number of civilian deaths, making it the deadliest in American history.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The technology and brutality of the Civil War foreshadowed the coming world wars.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The origins of the war were rooted in the desire of the Southern states to preserve the institution of slavery.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Historians in the 21st century overwhelmingly agree on the centrality of slavery in the conflict—at least for the Southern states.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] They disagree on the North's reasons for refusing to allow the Southern states to secede.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The pseudo-historical Lost Cause ideology denies that slavery was the principal cause of the secession, a view disproven by historical evidence, including the seceding states' own secession documents.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The principal political battle leading to Southern secession was over whether slavery would expand into the Western territories destined to become states.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Initially Congress had admitted new states into the Union in pairs, one slave and one free.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] This had kept a sectional balance in the Senate but not in the House of Representatives, as free states outstripped slave states in numbers of eligible voters.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Thus, at mid-19th century, the free-versus-slave status of the new territories was a critical issue, both for the North, where anti-slavery sentiment had grown, and for the South, where the fear of slavery's abolition had grown.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Another factor leading to secession and the formation of the Confederacy was the development of white Southern nationalism in the preceding decades.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The primary reason for the North to reject secession was to preserve the Union, a cause based on American nationalism.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Background factors in the run up to the Civil War were partisan politics, abolitionism, nullification versus secession, Southern and Northern nationalism, expansionism, economics, and modernization in the antebellum period.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Abraham Lincoln won the 1860 presidential election.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Southern leaders feared Lincoln would stop slavery's expansion and put it on a course toward extinction.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] His victory triggered declarations of secession by seven slave states of the Deep South, all of whose riverfront or coastal economies were based on cotton that was cultivated by slave labor.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln was not inaugurated until March 4, 1861, four months after his 1860 election, which afforded the South time to prepare for war.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Nationalists in the North and "Unionists" in the South refused to accept the declarations of secession, and no foreign government ever recognized the Confederacy.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The US government, under President James Buchanan, refused to relinquish the nation's forts, which the Confederacy claimed were located in their territory.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] According to Lincoln, the American people had demonstrated, beginning with their victory in the American Revolution and Revolutionary War and subsequent establishment of a sovereign nation, that they could successfully establish and administer a republic.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Yet, Lincoln believed, a question remained unanswered: Could the nation be maintained as a republic, with its government selected by vote of the people, in the face of internal attempts to destroy it or separate from it?
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln's election provoked South Carolina's legislature to call a state convention to consider secession.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] South Carolina had done more than any other state to advance the notion that a state had the right to nullify federal laws and even secede.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] On December 20, 1860, the convention unanimously voted to secede and adopted a secession declaration.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] It argued for states' rights for slave owners but complained about states' rights in the North in the form of resistance to the federal Fugitive Slave Act, claiming that Northern states were not fulfilling their obligations to assist in the return of fugitive slaves.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The "cotton states" of Mississippi, Florida, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas followed suit, seceding in January and February 1861.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Among the ordinances of secession, those of Texas, Alabama, and Virginia mentioned the plight of the "slaveholding states" at the hands of Northern abolitionists.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The rest made no mention of slavery but were brief announcements by the legislatures of the dissolution of ties to the Union.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] However, at least four—South Carolina, Mississippi, Georgia, and Texas—provided detailed reasons for their secession, all blaming the movement to abolish slavery and its influence over the North.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Southern states believed that the Fugitive Slave Clause made slaveholding a constitutional right.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] These states agreed to form a new federal government, the Confederate States of America, on February 4, 1861.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] They took control of federal forts and other properties within their boundaries, with little resistance from outgoing president James Buchanan, whose term ended on March 4.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Buchanan said the Dred Scott decision was proof the Southern states had no reason to secede and that the Union "was intended to be perpetual".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] He added, however, that "The power by force of arms to compel a State to remain in the Union" was not among the "enumerated powers granted to Congress".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] A quarter of the US army—the Texas garrison—was surrendered in February to state forces by its general, David E.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginia left the rest of Virginia and joined the Union as West Virginia because of the slavery issue.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] As Southerners resigned their Senate and House seats, Republicans could pass projects that had been blocked.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] These included the Morrill Tariff, land grant colleges, a Homestead Act, a transcontinental railroad, the National Bank Act, authorization of United States Notes by the Legal Tender Act of 1862, the end of slavery in the District of Columbia, and a ban on slavery in the territories.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The Revenue Act of 1861 introduced an income tax to help finance the war.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] In December 1860, the Crittenden Compromise was proposed to re-establish the Missouri Compromise line, by constitutionally banning slavery in territories to the north of it, while permitting it to the south.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The Compromise would likely have prevented secession, but Lincoln and the Republicans rejected it.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln stated that any compromise that would extend slavery would bring down the Union.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] A February peace conference met in Washington, proposing a solution similar to the Compromise; it was rejected by Congress.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The Republicans proposed the Corwin Amendment, an alternative, not to interfere with slavery where it existed, but the South regarded it as insufficient.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The remaining eight slave states rejected pleas to join the Confederacy, following a no-vote in Virginia's First Secessionist Convention on April 4.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] On March 4, Lincoln was sworn in as president.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] In his first inaugural address, he argued that the Constitution was a *more perfect union* than the earlier Articles of Confederation and Perpetual Union, was a binding contract, and that secession was "legally void".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] He did not intend to invade Southern states, nor to end slavery where it existed, but he said he would use force to maintain possession of federal property, including forts, arsenals, mints, and customhouses that had been seized.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] "The mails, unless repelled, will continue to be furnished in all parts of the Union." Where conditions did not allow peaceful enforcement of federal law, US marshals and judges would be withdrawn.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] No mention was made of bullion lost from mints.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] He stated that it would be US policy "to collect the duties and imposts"; "there will be no invasion, no using of force against or among the people anywhere" that would justify an armed revolution.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] His speech closed with a plea for restoration of the bonds of union, famously calling on "the mystic chords of memory" binding the two regions.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy sent delegates to Washington to negotiate a peace treaty.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln rejected negotiations, because he claimed that the Confederacy was not a legitimate government and to make a treaty with it would recognize it as such.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln instead attempted to negotiate directly with the governors of seceded states, whose administrations he continued to recognize.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Complicating Lincoln's attempts to defuse the crisis was Secretary of State William H.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Seward, who had been Lincoln's rival for the Republican nomination.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Embittered by his defeat, Seward agreed to support Lincoln's candidacy only after he was guaranteed the executive office then considered the second most powerful.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] In the early stages of Lincoln's presidency Seward held little regard for him, due to his perceived inexperience.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Seward viewed himself as the de facto head of government, the "prime minister" behind the throne.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Seward attempted to engage in unauthorized and indirect negotiations that failed.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln was determined to hold all remaining Union-occupied forts in the seceded states: Fort Pickens, Fort Jefferson, and Fort Taylor in Florida, and Fort Sumter in South Carolina.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The American Civil War began on April 12, 1861, when Confederate forces opened fire on the Union-held Fort Sumter.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Fort Sumter is located in the harbor of Charleston, South Carolina.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Its status had been contentious for months.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Outgoing president Buchanan had dithered in reinforcing its garrison, commanded by Major Robert Anderson.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Anderson took matters into his own hands and on December 26, 1860, under the cover of darkness, sailed the garrison from the poorly placed Fort Moultrie to the stalwart island Fort Sumter.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Anderson's actions catapulted him to hero status in the North.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] An attempt to resupply the fort on January 9, 1861, failed and nearly started the war then, but an informal truce held.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] On March 5, Lincoln was informed the fort was low on supplies.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Fort Sumter proved a key challenge to Lincoln's administration.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Back-channel dealing by Seward with the Confederates undermined Lincoln's decision-making; Seward wanted to pull out.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] But a firm hand by Lincoln tamed Seward, who was a staunch Lincoln ally thereafter.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln decided holding the fort, which would require reinforcing it, was the only workable option.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] On April 6, Lincoln informed the Governor of South Carolina that a ship with food but no ammunition would attempt to supply the fort.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] James McPherson describes this win-win approach as "the first sign of the mastery that would mark Lincoln's presidency"; the Union would win if it could resupply and hold the fort, and the South would be the aggressor if it opened fire on an unarmed ship supplying starving men.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] An April 9 Confederate cabinet meeting resulted in Davis ordering General P.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Beauregard to take the fort before supplies reached it.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] At 4:30 a.m. on April 12, Confederate forces fired the first of 4,000 shells at the fort; it fell the next day.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The loss of Fort Sumter lit a patriotic fire under the North.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] On April 15, Lincoln called on the states to field 75,000 militiamen for 90 days; impassioned Union states met the quotas quickly.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] On May 3, 1861, Lincoln called for an additional 42,000 volunteers for three years.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Shortly after this, Virginia, Tennessee, Arkansas, and North Carolina seceded and joined the Confederacy.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] To reward Virginia, the Confederate capital was moved to Richmond.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland, Delaware, Missouri, and Kentucky, known as the border states, were slave states that had not seceded and whose people had divided loyalties to the North and South, with some men enlisting in the Union Army and others in the Confederate Army.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginia may be compared to the border states because it had slavery after it separated from Virginia and was admitted to the Union on June 20, 1863, but it was admitted under a plan of gradual emancipation known as the Willey Amendment.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland's territory surrounded Washington, D.C., and could cut it off from the North.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] It had anti-Lincoln officials who tolerated anti-army rioting in Baltimore and the burning of bridges, both aimed at hindering the passage of troops to Washington, D.C., and the South.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland's legislature voted overwhelmingly to stay in the Union, but rejected hostilities with its southern neighbors, voting to close Maryland's rail lines to prevent their use for war.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln responded by establishing martial law and suspending habeas corpus in Maryland, along with sending in militia units.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] In *Ex parte Merryman*, Chief Justice Roger Taney found that only Congress could suspend habeas corpus, but Lincoln ignored his ruling.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln took control of Maryland and the District of Columbia by seizing prominent figures, including arresting one-third of the members of the Maryland General Assembly, who were pro-Confederate, on September 17, 1861, the day it intended to reconvene.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] All were held without trial at Fort McHenry in Baltimore.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] In September 1861, federal troops imprisoned a Baltimore newspaper editor, Frank Key Howard, after he criticized Lincoln in an editorial for ignoring Chief Justice Taney's ruling in *Ex parte Merryman*.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Howard wrote a book about his prison experiences, which was published early in 1863.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] It "stressed the crowded conditions and spartan hardships of prison life ... [and] likened the conditions in Fort Lafayette to those on 'a slave-ship, on the middle passage'".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] In Missouri, an elected convention on secession voted to remain in the Union.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] When pro-Confederate Governor Claiborne Fox Jackson called out the state militia, it was attacked by federal forces under General Nathaniel Lyon, who chased the governor and rest of the State Guard to the southwestern corner of Missouri (see Missouri secession).
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Early in the war the Confederacy controlled southern Missouri through the Confederate government of Missouri but was driven out after 1862.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] In the resulting vacuum, the convention on secession reconvened and took power as the Unionist provisional government of Missouri.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Kentucky did not secede but declared itself neutral.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] When Confederate forces entered in September 1861, its neutrality ended and the state reaffirmed its Union status while maintaining slavery.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Its jurisdiction extended only as far as Confederate battle lines in the Commonwealth, which at its greatest extent was over half the state, and it went into exile after October 1862.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] After Virginia's secession, a Unionist government in Wheeling asked 48 counties to vote on an ordinance to create a new state in October 1861.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] A voter turnout of 34 percent approved the statehood bill (96 percent approving).
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Twenty-four secessionist counties were included in the new state, and the ensuing guerrilla war engaged about 40,000 federal troops for much of the war.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Congress admitted West Virginia to the Union on June 20, 1863.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginians provided about 20,000 soldiers to each side in the war.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] A Unionist secession attempt occurred in East Tennessee but was suppressed by the Confederacy, which arrested over 3,000 men suspected of loyalty to the Union; they were held without trial.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The Civil War was marked by intense and frequent battles.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Over four years, 237 named battles were fought, along with many smaller actions, often characterized by their bitter intensity and high casualties.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Historian John Keegan described it as "one of the most ferocious wars ever fought", where in many cases the only target was the enemy's soldiers.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] As the Confederate states organized, the US Army numbered 16,000, while Northern governors began mobilizing their militias.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederate Congress authorized up to 100,000 troops in February.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] By May, Jefferson Davis was pushing for another 100,000 soldiers for one year or the duration, and the US Congress responded in kind.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] In the first year of the war, both sides had more volunteers than they could effectively train and equip.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] After the initial enthusiasm faded, relying on young men who came of age each year was not enough.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Both sides enacted draft laws (conscription) to encourage or force volunteering, though relatively few were drafted.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy passed a draft law in April 1862 for men aged 18 to 35, with exemptions for overseers, government officials, and clergymen.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The US Congress followed in July, authorizing a militia draft within states that could not meet their quota with volunteers.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] European immigrants joined the Union Army in large numbers, including 177,000 born in Germany and 144,000 in Ireland.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] About 50,000 Canadians served, around 2,500 of whom were black.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] When the Emancipation Proclamation went into effect in January 1863, ex-slaves were energetically recruited to meet state quotas.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] States and local communities offered higher cash bonuses for white volunteers.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Congress tightened the draft law in March 1863.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Men selected in the draft could provide substitutes or, until mid-1864, pay commutation money.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Many eligibles pooled their money to cover the cost of anyone drafted.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Families used the substitute provision to select which man should go into the army and which should stay home.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] There was much evasion and resistance to the draft, especially in Catholic areas.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The New York City draft riots in July 1863 involved Irish immigrants who had been signed up as citizens to swell the vote of the city's Democratic political machine, not realizing it made them liable for the draft.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Of the 168,649 men procured for the Union through the draft, 117,986 were substitutes, leaving only 50,663 who were conscripted.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] In the North and South, draft laws were highly unpopular.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] In the North, some 120,000 men evaded conscription, many fleeing to Canada, and another 280,000 soldiers deserted during the war.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] At least 100,000 Southerners deserted, about 10 percent of the total.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Southern desertion was high because many soldiers were more concerned about the fate of their local area than the Southern cause.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] In the North, "bounty jumpers" enlisted to collect the generous bonus, deserted, then re-enlisted under a different name for a second bonus; 141 were caught and executed.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] From a tiny frontier force in 1860, the Union and Confederate armies grew into the "largest and most efficient armies in the world" within a few years.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Some European observers at the time dismissed them as amateur and unprofessional, but historian John Keegan concluded that each outmatched the French, Prussian, and Russian armies, and without the Atlantic, could have threatened any of them with defeat.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Unionism was strong in certain areas within the Confederacy.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] As many as 100,000 men living in states under Confederate control served in the Union Army or pro-Union guerrilla groups.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Although they came from all classes, most Southern Unionists differed socially, culturally, and economically from their region's dominant prewar, slave-owning planter class.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] At the beginning of the Civil War, a parole system operated, under which captives agreed not to fight until exchanged.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] They were held in camps run by their army, paid, but not allowed to perform any military duties.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The system of exchanges collapsed in 1863 when the Confederacy refused to exchange black prisoners.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] After that, approximately 56,000 of the 409,000 POWs died in prisons, accounting for 10 percent of the conflict's fatalities.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Leonard writes that between 500 and 1,000 women enlisted as soldiers on both sides, disguised as men.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Women also served as spies, resistance activists, nurses, and hospital personnel.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Women served on the Union hospital ship *Red Rover* and nursed Union and Confederate troops at field hospitals.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Mary Edwards Walker, the only woman ever to receive the Medal of Honor, served in the Union Army and was given the medal for treating the wounded during the war.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] One woman, Jennie Hodgers, fought for the Union under the name Albert D.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] After she returned to civilian life, she continued to live as a man until she died in 1915 at the age of 71.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] During the war, women in the North advocated for social reforms and created ladies' aid societies, also called soldiers' aid societies, which provided supplies to soldiers on the battlefield and cared for sick and wounded soldiers.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Women in the North also held military rallies, village parades, and charity bazaars.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Anthony saw that supporting the war effort was a way to pave the future for women's suffrage movements.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] In her appeal to Northern women's loyalty, Anthony challenged the inconsistencies of the nation's founding ideal and its actual practices concerning equality among women.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Northern women during the Civil War also made great strides in the workforce, as they helped contribute to the war effort by stepping into roles that were traditionally held by men.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] While women rarely worked in factories before the war, many filled men's places as they felt they could erase some of the boundaries that separated them from male preserves of power.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Women were important in the workforce as they prepared and packed provisions, sewed uniforms and havelocks, and knitted socks and mittens.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] By entering these new environments, women made significant progress in the fight for women's equality in the workforce.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Northern women were also essential in the wartime support, as they were active participants in the war narrative.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] While women were not allowed to fight on the battlefield in the Civil War, they exhibited a patriotism that gave them the strength to maintain courage for themselves as well as their households.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] While their men were off at war, Northern women created a landscape that emphasized love, sacrifice, and the nurturing of men's courage.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] This is demonstrated in feminized war literature that encouraged, expressed, and valorized men's patriotism.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Women's unwavering encouragement and affection towards fighting men became a cornerstone of the war effort as it helped sustain the spirits of the men on the frontlines.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate women during the Civil War focused on preserving the central economic institution of the Old South: the plantation.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] With so many men away at war, women were left with the land and the slaves.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] While some women hired male overseers to assist them in directing and maintaining newly female-headed plantations, other women decided to stay at the plantations and run the plantations themselves.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Southern women became focused on keeping the economic structure of the South as they dealt with increasingly rebellious slaves.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The South relied on enslaved labor because it was an agrarian economy.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] A good number of enslaved men labored for the Confederate army during the war, which meant that enslaved women and children were increasingly at the center of the work force on the plantations.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] White Southern women struggled to maintain morale on the home front as they dealt with problems without men.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Although Southern women were devoted to the Confederacy, many requested that their sons and husbands be discharged from the military to help them at home.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Eliza Adams wrote to the Confederate government to appeal for exemptions for her sons' military service, as she had sent five sons and also sons-in-laws to fight for the Confederacy.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Southern women were torn between their patriotic ideals and their daily realities of life on the home front.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The Union Navy in 1861 was relatively small but, by 1865, expanded rapidly to 6,000 officers, 45,000 sailors, and 671 vessels totaling 510,396 tons.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Its mission was to blockade Confederate ports, control the river system, defend against Confederate raiders on the high seas, and be ready for a possible war with the British Royal Navy.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The main riverine war was fought in the West, where major rivers gave access to the Confederate heartland.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The US Navy eventually controlled the Red, Tennessee, Cumberland, Mississippi, and Ohio rivers.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] In the East, the Navy shelled Confederate forts and supported coastal army operations.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The Civil War occurred during the early stages of the industrial revolution, leading to naval innovations, including the ironclad warship.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy, recognizing the need to counter the Union's naval superiority, built or converted over 130 vessels, including 26 ironclads.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Despite these efforts, Confederate ships were largely unsuccessful against Union ironclads.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The Union Navy used timberclads, tinclads, and armored gunboats.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy experimented with the submarine CSS *Hunley*, which proved unsuccessful, and with the ironclad CSS *Virginia*, rebuilt from the sunken Union ship *Merrimack*.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] On March 8, 1862, *Virginia* inflicted significant damage on the Union's wooden fleet, but the next day, the first Union ironclad, USS *Monitor*, arrived to challenge it in the Chesapeake Bay.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The resulting three-hour Battle of Hampton Roads was a draw, proving ironclads were effective warships.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy scuttled the *Virginia* to prevent its capture, while the Union built many copies of the *Monitor*.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy's efforts to obtain warships from Great Britain failed, as Britain had no interest in selling warships to a nation at war with a stronger enemy and feared souring relations with the US.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] By early 1861, General Winfield Scott had devised the Anaconda Plan to win the war with minimal bloodshed, calling for a blockade of the Confederacy to suffocate the South into surrender.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln adopted parts of the plan but opted for a more active war strategy.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] In April 1861, Lincoln announced a blockade of all Southern ports; commercial ships could not get insurance, ending regular traffic.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The South blundered by embargoing cotton exports before the blockade was fully effective; by the time they reversed this decision, it was too late.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] "King Cotton" was dead, as the South could export less than 10% of its cotton.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The blockade shut down the ten Confederate seaports with railheads that moved almost all the cotton.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] By June 1861, warships were stationed off the principal Southern ports, and a year later nearly 300 ships were in service.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederates began the war short on military supplies, which the agrarian South could not produce in adequate numbers.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Northern arms manufacturers were restricted by an embargo, ending existing and future contracts with the South.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy turned to foreign sources, connecting with financiers and companies like S.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Isaac, Campbell & Company and the London Armoury Company in Britain, becoming the Confederacy's main source of arms.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] To transport arms safely to the Confederacy, British investors built small, fast, steam-driven blockade runners that traded arms and supplies from Britain, through Bermuda, Cuba, and the Bahamas in exchange for high-priced cotton.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Many were lightweight and designed for speed, only carrying small amounts of cotton back to England.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] When the Union Navy seized a blockade runner, the ship and cargo were condemned as a prize of war and sold, with proceeds given to the Navy sailors; the captured crewmen, mostly British, were released.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The Southern economy nearly collapsed during the war due to multiple factors, the most notable being severe food shortages, failing railroads, loss of control over key rivers, foraging by Northern armies, and the seizure of animals and crops by Confederate forces.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Historians agree the blockade was a major factor in ruining the Confederate economy; however, Wise argues blockade runners provided enough of a lifeline to allow Robert E.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Lee, a Confederate general, to continue fighting for additional months, as a result of supplies that included 400,000 rifles, lead, blankets, and boots that the Confederate economy could no longer supply.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederate cotton crop became nearly useless, which cut off the Confederacy's primary income source.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Critical imports were scarce, and coastal trade also largely ended.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The blockade's success was not measured by the few ships, which slipped through, but by the thousands that never tried.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] European merchant ships could not obtain insurance for their ships and transport, and were too slow to evade the blockade, leading them to cease docking in Confederate ports.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] To fight an offensive war, the Confederacy purchased arms in Britain and converted British-built ships into commerce raiders, which targeted United States Merchant Marine ships in the Atlantic and Pacific oceans.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy smuggled 600,000 arms, enabling it to continue fighting for two more years.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] As insurance rates soared, American-flagged ships largely ceased traveling in international waters, though some were reflagged with European flags, which allowed them to continue operating.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] After the conclusion of the Civil War, the US government demanded Britain reimburse it for the damage caused by blockade runners and raiders outfitted in British ports.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Britain paid the US$15 million in 1871, which covered costs associated with commerce raiding but nothing more.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Although the Confederacy hoped Britain and France would join them against the Union, this was never likely, so they sought to bring them in as mediators.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The Union worked to block this and threatened war against any country that recognized the Confederacy.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] In 1861, Southerners voluntarily embargoed cotton shipments, hoping to start an economic depression in Europe that would force Britain to enter the war, but this failed.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Worse, Europe turned to Egypt and India for cotton, which they found superior, hindering the South's postwar recovery.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Cotton diplomacy proved a failure, because Europe had a surplus of cotton, while the 1860–62 crop failures in Europe made the North's grain exports critically important.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] It also helped turn European opinion against the Confederacy.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] It was said that "King Corn was more powerful than King Cotton", as US grain increased from a quarter to almost half of British imports.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Meanwhile, the war created jobs for arms makers, ironworkers, and ships to transport weapons.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln's administration initially struggled to appeal to European public opinion.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] At first, diplomats explained that the US was not committed to ending slavery and emphasized legal arguments about the unconstitutionality of secession.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate representatives, however, focused on their struggle for liberty, commitment to free trade, and the essential role of cotton in the European economy.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The European aristocracy was "absolutely gleeful in pronouncing the American debacle as proof that the entire experiment in popular government had failed.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] European government leaders welcomed the fragmentation of the ascendant American Republic." However, a European public with liberal sensibilities remained, which the US sought to appeal to by building connections with the international press.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] By 1861, Union diplomats like Carl Schurz realized emphasizing the war against slavery was the Union's most effective moral asset in swaying European public opinion.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Seward was concerned an overly radical case for reunification would distress European merchants with cotton interests; even so, he supported a widespread campaign of public diplomacy.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] US minister to Britain Charles Francis Adams proved adept and convinced Britain not to challenge the Union blockade.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy purchased warships from commercial shipbuilders in Britain, with the most famous being the CSS *Alabama*, which caused considerable damage and led to serious postwar disputes.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] However, public opinion against slavery in Britain created a political liability for politicians, where the anti-slavery movement was powerful.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] War loomed in late 1861 between the US and Britain over the *Trent* Affair, which began when US Navy personnel boarded the British ship *Trent* and seized two Confederate diplomats.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] However, London and Washington smoothed this over after Lincoln released the two men.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Prince Albert left his deathbed to issue diplomatic instructions to Lord Lyons during the *Trent* Affair.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] His request was honored, and, as a result, the British response to the US was toned down, helping avert war.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] In 1862, the British government considered mediating between the Union and Confederacy, though such an offer would have risked war with the US.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] British prime minister Lord Palmerston reportedly read *Uncle Tom's Cabin* three times when deciding what his decision would be.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The Union victory at the Battle of Antietam caused the British to delay this decision.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] The Emancipation Proclamation increased the political liability of supporting the Confederacy.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Realizing that Washington could not intervene in Mexico as long as the Confederacy controlled Texas, France invaded Mexico in 1861 and installed the Habsburg Austrian archduke Maximilian I as emperor.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Washington repeatedly protested France's violation of the Monroe Doctrine.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Despite sympathy for the Confederacy, France's seizure of Mexico deterred it from war with the Union.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate offers late in the war to end slavery in return for diplomatic recognition were not seriously considered by London or Paris.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] After 1863, the Polish revolt against Russia further distracted the European powers and ensured they remained neutral.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] Russia supported the Union, largely because it believed the US counterbalanced its geopolitical rival, the UK.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p01] In 1863, the Imperial Russian Navy's Baltic and Pacific fleets wintered in the American ports of New York and San Francisco, respectively.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Eastern theater refers to the military operations east of the Appalachian Mountains, including Virginia, West Virginia, Maryland, and Pennsylvania, the District of Columbia, and the coastal fortifications and seaports of North Carolina.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan took command of the Union Army of the Potomac on July 26, 1861, and the war began in earnest in 1862.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Ohio forces would advance through Kentucky into Tennessee.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Missouri Department would drive south along the Mississippi River.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The westernmost attack would originate from Kansas.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The primary Confederate force in the Eastern theater was the Army of Northern Virginia.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Army originated as the (Confederate) Army of the Potomac, which was organized on June 20, 1861, from all operational forces in Northern Virginia.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] On July 20 and 21, the Army of the Shenandoah and forces from the District of Harpers Ferry were added.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Units from the Army of the Northwest were merged into the Army of the Potomac between March 14 and May 17, 1862.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of the Potomac was renamed *Army of Northern Virginia* on March 14.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of the Peninsula was merged into it on April 12, 1862.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] When Virginia declared its secession in April 1861, Robert E.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Lee chose to follow his home state, despite his desire for the country to remain intact and an offer of a senior Union command.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] In his four-volume biography of Lee published in 1934 and 1935, historian Douglas S.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Freeman wrote that the army received its final name from Lee when he issued orders assuming command on June 1, 1862.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] However, Freeman wrote, Lee corresponded with Brigadier General Joseph E.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston, his predecessor in army command, before that date and referred to Johnston's command as the Army of Northern Virginia.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Part of the confusion results from the fact that Johnston commanded the Department of Northern Virginia as of October 22, 1861, and the name Army of Northern Virginia was seen as an informal consequence of its parent department's name.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Jefferson Davis and Johnston did not adopt the name, but the organization of units as of March 14 was clearly the same organization that Lee received on June 1, and is generally referred to as the Army of Northern Virginia, even if that is correct only in retrospect.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] On July 4 at Harper's Ferry, Colonel Thomas J.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson assigned Jeb Stuart command of all cavalry companies of the Army of the Shenandoah, and Jackson eventually commanded the Army of Northern Virginia's cavalry.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Called the "Philippi Races" because of its brevity, Philippi, Virginia (now Philippi, WV) was the scene of the first organized land action of the American Civil War, on June 3, 1861.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] In July 1861, in the first in a series of prominent battles in the war, Union Army troops commanded by Maj.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Irvin McDowell attacked Confederate forces, which were under the command of Beauregard near the national capital in Washington.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederacy repelled the attack in the First Battle of Bull Run.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] At the beginning of the battle, the Union appeared to hold the upper hand.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Union Army routed Confederate forces, then holding defensive positions, but Confederate reinforcements under Joseph E.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston arrived from the Shenandoah Valley by railroad, and the battle's course quickly changed.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] A brigade of Virginians, commanded by Thomas J.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson, then a relatively unknown brigadier general from Virginia Military Institute, stood its ground, leading to Jackson earning the nickname "Stonewall".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln urged the Union Army to commence offensive operations against Confederate forces, which led General George B.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan, in the spring of 1862, to attack Virginia by way of the peninsula between the York River and James River southeast of Richmond.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan's army reached the gates of Richmond in the Peninsula campaign.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Also in the spring of 1862, in Shenandoah Valley, Jackson led his Valley Campaign, during which he employed rapid and unpredictable movements on interior lines.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson's 17,000 troops marched 646 miles (1,040 km) in 48 days, during which they won minor battles as they engaged three Union armies, comprising 52,000 men, including those of Nathaniel P.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Frémont, preventing them from reinforcing the Union offensive against Richmond.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The swiftness of Jackson's troops earned them the nickname foot cavalry.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston halted McClellan's advance at the Battle of Seven Pines, but he was wounded in the battle, and Robert E.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Lee and his senior subordinates, James Longstreet and Stonewall Jackson, defeated McClellan in the Seven Days Battles, forcing McClellan's retreat.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] During the Northern Virginia Campaign, which included the Second Battle of Bull Run, Confederate forces registered another important military victory.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan resisted General-in-Chief Halleck's orders to send reinforcements to John Pope's Union Army of Virginia, which enabled Lee's Confederate forces to defeat twice the number of combined enemy troops.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Emboldened by Second Bull Run, Confederate forces launched their first invasion of the North in the Maryland Campaign during which Lee led 45,000 Army of Northern Virginia troops across the Potomac River into Maryland on September 5.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln then restored Pope's troops to McClellan, and McClellan and Lee clashed in the Battle of Antietam near Sharpsburg, Maryland, on September 17, 1862, which proved the bloodiest single day in both the Civil War and US military history.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan failed to respond in any measurable way to Lee's attempt to invade the North at Antietam, leading to his replacement by Maj.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Burnside led Union Army troops in the Battle of Fredericksburg, where they were defeated on December 13, 1862.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Over 12,000 Union soldiers were killed or wounded during futile attempts by Union troops to launch frontal assaults against Marye's Heights.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] After the battle, Burnside was replaced by Maj.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Hooker, too, proved unable to defeat Lee's army; despite having more than twice as many troops as Lee, Hooker's Chancellorsville Campaign proved ineffective, and he was soundly defeated in the Battle of Chancellorsville, which was fought between April 30 and May 6, 1863.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Chancellorsville is known as Lee's "perfect battle" because his risky decision to divide his army paid off.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] During the Battle of Chancellorsville, Stonewall Jackson was shot in his left arm and right hand by friendly fire, leading to the amputation of his arm, and he died of pneumonia.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The fiercest fighting of the battle—and the second bloodiest day of the Civil War—occurred on May 3 as Lee launched multiple attacks against the Union position at Chancellorsville.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] That same day, John Sedgwick advanced across the Rappahannock River, defeated the small Confederate force at Marye's Heights in the Second Battle of Fredericksburg, and then moved westward, but Confederate forces succeeded in delaying Union forces in the Battle of Salem Church.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] George Meade during Lee's second invasion of the North, in June.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] In the Battle of Gettysburg, which proved the war's bloodiest and one of its most strategically significant, Meade defeated Lee in a three-day battle between July 1 and 3, 1863.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of Gettysburg caused over 50,000 Union and Confederate casualties, but also proved the war's turning point, altering the course of the war in the Union's favor.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Pickett's Charge, launched July 3, on the final day of the Battle of Gettysburg, is considered the high-water mark of the Confederacy, representing the collapse of any credible prospect that the Confederacy could prevail in the war.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] At Gettysburg, Lee's Army of Northern Virginia suffered 28,000 casualties versus Meade's 23,000, and Lee was repelled in a failed attempt to invade and occupy Union territory.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Western theater refers to military operations between the Appalachian Mountains and the Mississippi River, including Alabama, Georgia, Florida, Mississippi, North Carolina, Kentucky, South Carolina, Tennessee, and parts of Louisiana.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The primary Union forces in this theater were the Army of the Tennessee and Army of the Cumberland, named for the two rivers, Tennessee River and Cumberland River.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] After Meade's inconclusive fall campaign, Lincoln turned to the Western theater for new leadership.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] At the same time, the Confederate stronghold of Vicksburg surrendered, giving the Union control of the Mississippi River, permanently isolating the western Confederacy, and producing the new leader Lincoln needed, Ulysses S.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of Tennessee, which served as the primary Confederate force in the Western theater, was formed on November 20, 1862, when General Braxton Bragg renamed the former Army of Mississippi.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] While Confederate forces had successes in the Eastern theater, they were defeated many times in the West.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's key strategist and tactician in the West was Ulysses S.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Grant, who led the Union to victories in battles at Fort Henry (February 6, 1862) and Fort Donelson (February 11 to 16, 1862), earning him the nickname of "Unconditional Surrender" Grant.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] With these victories, the Union gained control of the Tennessee and Cumberland Rivers.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Nathan Bedford Forrest rallied nearly 4,000 Confederate troops and led them to escape across the Cumberland River.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Nashville and central Tennessee fell to the Union, leading to attrition of local food supplies and livestock and a breakdown in social organization.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate general Leonidas Polk subsequently invaded Columbus, Kentucky, which ended Kentucky's policy of neutrality and turned it against the Confederacy.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Grant used river transport and Andrew Hull Foote's gunboats of the Western Flotilla, threatening the Confederacy's "Gibraltar of the West" in Columbus, Kentucky.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Although rebuffed at Belmont, Grant cut off Columbus.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces, lacking their gunboats, were forced to retreat and the Union took control of west Kentucky and opened Tennessee in March 1862.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] At the Battle of Shiloh, in Shiloh, Tennessee, in April 1862, Confederate forces launched a surprise attack on Union forces, pushing them back to the Tennessee River as night fell.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Over that night, however, the Navy landed reinforcements, and Grant counterattacked.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Grant and the Union ultimately won a decisive victory in the first battle with a high number of casualties in what proved to be the first in a series of such battles.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces lost Albert Sidney Johnston, considered their finest general, before Lee emerged to assume command.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] One of the early Union objectives was to capture the Mississippi River, which would permit it to cut the Confederacy in half.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Mississippi was opened to Union traffic to the southern border of Tennessee after it took Island No.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] 10, New Madrid, Missouri, and then Memphis, Tennessee.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] In April 1862, the Union Navy captured New Orleans.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] "The key to the river was New Orleans, the South's largest port [and] greatest industrial center." US naval forces under Farragut ran past Confederate defenses south of New Orleans.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces abandoned the city, giving the Union a critical anchor in the deep South, which allowed Union forces to move up the Mississippi.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Memphis fell to Union forces on June 6, 1862, allowing it to serve as a key base for further Union advances south along the Mississippi.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] On the Mississippi River, the Union took every fortress city with the exception of Vicksburg, Mississippi.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] But Confederate control of Vicksburg was sufficient in preventing the Union from controlling the entire river.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Bragg's second invasion of Kentucky in the Confederate Heartland Offensive included initial successes, including Kirby Smith's triumph in the Battle of Richmond and the capture of the Kentucky capital of Frankfort, Kentucky, on September 3, 1862.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The campaign ended with a meaningless victory over Maj.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Don Carlos Buell at the Battle of Perryville, and Bragg was forced to end his attempt to invade and control Kentucky.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Lacking logistical support and infantry recruits, Bragg was instead forced to retreat, and ended up being narrowly defeated by Maj.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] William Rosecrans in the Battle of Stones River in Tennessee in what proved to be the culmination of the Stones River Campaign.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] US naval forces assisted Grant in the long, complex Vicksburg Campaign, which resulted in Confederate forces surrendering in the Battle of Vicksburg in July 1863, which cemented Union control of the Mississippi River in one of the war's turning points.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The one clear Confederate victory in the West was the Battle of Chickamauga.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] After Rosecrans' successful Tullahoma Campaign, Bragg, reinforced by Lt.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] James Longstreet's Corps, defeated Rosecrans, despite the defensive stand of Maj.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Rosecrans retreated to Chattanooga, Tennessee, where Bragg was then besieged in the Chattanooga campaign.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Grant marched to the relief of Rosecrans, where he led the defeat of Bragg in the Third Battle of Chattanooga, eventually causing Longstreet to abandon his Knoxville Campaign and driving Confederate forces out of Tennessee and opening a route to Atlanta and the heart of the Confederacy.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Trans-Mississippi theater refers to military operations west of the Mississippi, encompassing most of Missouri, Arkansas, most of Louisiana, and the Indian Territory in present-day Oklahoma.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's command was the Trans-Mississippi Division, or the Military Division of West Mississippi.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The first major battle of the Trans-Mississippi theater was the Battle of Wilson's Creek (August 1861).
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederates were driven from Missouri early in the war as a result of the Battle of Pea Ridge.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Extensive guerrilla warfare characterized the trans-Mississippi region, as the Confederacy lacked the troops and logistics to support regular armies that could challenge Union control.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Roving Confederate bands such as Quantrill's Raiders terrorized the countryside, striking military installations and civilian settlements.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The "Sons of Liberty" and "Order of the American Knights" attacked pro-Union people, elected officeholders, and unarmed uniformed soldiers.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] These partisans could not be driven out of Missouri, until an entire regular Union infantry division was engaged.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] By 1864, these violent activities harmed the nationwide antiwar movement organizing against the re-election of Lincoln.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Missouri not only stayed in the Union, but Lincoln took 70 percent of the vote to win re-election.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Small-scale military actions south and west of Missouri sought to control Indian Territory and New Mexico Territory for the Union.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of Glorieta Pass was the decisive battle of the New Mexico Campaign.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Union repulsed Confederate incursions into New Mexico in 1862, and the exiled Arizona government withdrew into Texas.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] In the Indian Territory, civil war broke out within tribes.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] About 12,000 Indian warriors fought for the Confederacy but fewer for the Union.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The most prominent Cherokee was Brigadier General Stand Watie, the last Confederate general to surrender.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] After the fall of Vicksburg in July 1863, Jefferson Davis informed General Kirby Smith in Texas that he could expect no further help from east of the Mississippi.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Although he lacked resources to beat Union armies, he built up a formidable arsenal at Tyler, along with his own Kirby Smithdom economy, a virtual "independent fiefdom" in Texas, including railroad construction and international smuggling.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Union, in turn, did not directly engage him.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's 1864 Red River Campaign to take Shreveport, Louisiana, failed and Texas remained in Confederate hands throughout the war.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The lower seaboard theater refers to military and naval operations that occurred near the coastal areas of the Southeast as well as the southern part of the Mississippi.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Union naval activities were dictated by the Anaconda Plan.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] One of the earliest battles was fought in November 1861 at Port Royal Sound, south of Charleston.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Much of the war along the South Carolina coast concentrated on capturing Charleston.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] In attempting to capture Charleston, the Union military tried two approaches: by land over James or Morris Islands or through the harbor.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] However, the Confederates were able to drive back each attack.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] A famous land attack was the Second Battle of Fort Wagner, in which the 54th Massachusetts Infantry took part.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Union suffered a serious defeat, losing 1,515 soldiers while the Confederates lost only 174.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] However, the 54th was hailed for its valor, which encouraged the general acceptance of the recruitment of African American soldiers into the Union Army, which reinforced the Union's numerical advantage.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Fort Pulaski on the Georgia coast was an early target for the Union navy.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Following the capture of Port Royal, an expedition was organized with engineer troops under the command of Captain Quincy Adams Gillmore, forcing a Confederate surrender.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Union army occupied the fort for the rest of the war after repairing it.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] In April 1862, a Union naval task force commanded by Commander David Dixon Porter attacked Forts Jackson and St.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Philip, which guarded the river approach to New Orleans from the south.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] While part of the fleet bombarded the forts, other vessels forced a break in the obstructions in the river and enabled the rest of the fleet to steam upriver to the city.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Benjamin Butler landed near the forts and forced their surrender.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Butler's controversial command of New Orleans earned him the nickname "Beast".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The following year, the Union Army of the Gulf commanded by Maj.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Banks laid siege to Port Hudson for nearly eight weeks, the longest siege in US military history.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederates attempted to defend with the Bayou Teche Campaign but surrendered after Vicksburg.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] These surrenders gave the Union control over the Mississippi.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Several skirmishes but no major battles were fought in Florida.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The biggest was the Battle of Olustee in early 1864.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Pacific coast theater refers to military operations on the Pacific Ocean and in the states and territories west of the Continental Divide.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] At the beginning of 1864, Lincoln made Grant commander of all Union armies.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Grant made his headquarters with the Army of the Potomac and put Maj.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] William Tecumseh Sherman in command of most of the western armies.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Grant understood the concept of total war and believed, along with Lincoln and Sherman, that only the utter defeat of Confederate forces and their economic base would end the war.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] This was total war not in killing civilians, but in injuring the Confederacy's capacity to produce and transport the supplies needed to continue the war.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman, at Grant's direction, seized provisions and destroyed homes, farms, and railroads, which Grant said "would otherwise have gone to the support of secession and rebellion.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Grant devised a coordinated strategy that would strike at the entire Confederacy from multiple directions.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Generals Meade and Benjamin Butler were ordered to move against Lee near Richmond, General Franz Sigel was to attack the Shenandoah Valley, General Sherman was to capture Atlanta and march to the Atlantic Ocean, Generals George Crook and William W.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Averell were to operate against railroad supply lines in West Virginia, and Maj.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Grant's army set out on the Overland Campaign intending to draw Lee into a defense of Richmond, where they would attempt to pin down and destroy the Confederate army.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Union army first attempted to maneuver past Lee and fought several battles, notably at the Wilderness, Spotsylvania, and Cold Harbor.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] These resulted in heavy losses on both sides and forced Lee's Confederates to fall back repeatedly.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] At the Battle of Yellow Tavern, the Confederates lost Jeb Stuart.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] An attempt to outflank Lee from the south failed under Butler, who was trapped inside the Bermuda Hundred river bend.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Each battle resulted in setbacks for the Union that mirrored those they had suffered under prior generals, though unlike them, Grant chose to fight on rather than retreat.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Grant was tenacious and kept pressing Lee's Army of Northern Virginia back to Richmond.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] While Lee was preparing for an attack on Richmond, Grant unexpectedly turned south to cross the James River and began the protracted Siege of Petersburg, where the two armies engaged in trench warfare for over nine months.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] To deny the Confederacy continued use of the Shenandoah Valley as a base from which to launch invasions of Maryland and the Washington area, and to threaten Lee's supply lines for his forces, Grant launched the Valley campaigns in May 1864.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Sigel were repelled at the Battle of New Market by Confederate Gen.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of New Market was the Confederacy's last major victory, and included a charge by teenage VMI cadets.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] After relieving Sigel, and following mixed performances by his successor, Grant finally found a commander, General Philip Sheridan, aggressive enough to prevail against the army of Maj.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] After a cautious start, Sheridan defeated Early in a series of battles in September and October 1864, including a decisive defeat at the Battle of Cedar Creek.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Sheridan then proceeded through that winter to destroy the agricultural base of the Shenandoah Valley, a strategy similar to the tactics Sherman later employed in Georgia.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Meanwhile, Sherman maneuvered from Chattanooga to Atlanta, defeating Confederate Generals Joseph E.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The fall of Atlanta on September 2, 1864, guaranteed the reelection of Lincoln.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Hood left the Atlanta area to swing around and menace Sherman's supply lines and invade Tennessee in the Franklin–Nashville Campaign.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] John Schofield defeated Hood at the Battle of Franklin, and George H.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Thomas dealt Hood a massive defeat at the Battle of Nashville, effectively destroying Hood's army.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Leaving Atlanta, and his base of supplies, Sherman's army marched, with no destination set, laying waste to about 20 percent of the farms in Georgia on his March to the Sea.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] He reached the Atlantic at Savannah, Georgia, in December 1864.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman's army was followed by thousands of freed slaves; there were no major battles along the march.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman turned north through South Carolina and North Carolina in his Carolinas campaign, to approach the Confederate Virginia lines from the south, increasing the pressure on Lee's army.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Lee's army, thinned by desertion and casualties, was now much smaller than Grant's.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] One last Confederate attempt to break the Union hold on Petersburg failed at the decisive Battle of Five Forks on April 1.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Union now controlled the entire perimeter surrounding Richmond–Petersburg, completely cutting it off from the Confederacy.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Realizing the capital was now lost, Lee's army and the Confederate government were forced to evacuate.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederate capital fell on April 2–3, to the Union XXV Corps, composed of black troops.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The remaining Confederate units fled west after a defeat at Sayler's Creek on April 6.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] front page celebrated Lee's surrender, headlining how Grant let Confederate officers retain their sidearms and "paroled" the Confederate officers and men.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] News of Lee's April 9 surrender reached this southern newspaper (Savannah, Georgia) on April 15—after the April 14 shooting of President Lincoln.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The article quotes Grant's terms of surrender.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Lee did not intend to surrender, but planned to regroup at Appomattox Station, where supplies were to be waiting, and then continue the war.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Grant chased Lee and got in front of him, so that when Lee's army reached the village of Appomattox Court House, they were surrounded.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] After an initial battle, Lee decided the fight was hopeless, and surrendered his Army of Northern Virginia to Grant on April 9, 1865, during a conference at the McLean House.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] In an untraditional gesture and as a sign of Grant's respect and anticipation of peacefully restoring Confederate states to the Union, Lee was permitted to keep his sword and horse, Traveller.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] His men were paroled, and a chain of Confederate surrenders began.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] On April 14, 1865, Lincoln was shot by John Wilkes Booth, a Confederate sympathizer.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's vice president, Andrew Johnson, was unharmed, because his would-be assassin, George Atzerodt, lost his nerve, so Johnson was immediately sworn in as president.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Meanwhile, Confederate forces across the South surrendered, as news of Lee's surrender reached them.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] On April 26, the same day Sergeant Boston Corbett killed Booth at a tobacco barn, Johnston surrendered nearly 90,000 troops of the Army of Tennessee to Sherman at Bennett Place, near present-day Durham, North Carolina.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] It proved to be the largest surrender of Confederate forces.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] On May 4, all remaining Confederate forces in Alabama, Mississippi, and Louisiana east of the Mississippi, under the command of Lt.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate president Davis was captured in retreat at Irwinville, Georgia on May 10.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The final land battle was fought on May 13, 1865, at the Battle of Palmito Ranch in Texas.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Buckner, acting for Edmund Smith, signed a military convention surrendering Confederate forces in the Trans-Mississippi Department.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] This date is often cited by contemporaries and historians as the effective end date of the war.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] On June 2, with most of his troops having already gone home, a reluctant Kirby Smith had little choice but to sign the official surrender document.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] General Stand Watie became the last Confederate general to surrender his forces.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Gordon Granger announced General Order No.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] 3, bringing the Emancipation Proclamation into effect in Texas and freeing the last slaves of the Confederacy.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The anniversary of this date is now celebrated as Juneteenth.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The naval part of the war ended more slowly.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Britain finally responded on June 6, by transmitting a letter from Foreign Secretary John Russell, 1st Earl Russell, to the Lords of the Admiralty withdrawing rights to Confederate warships to enter British ports and waters.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] US Secretary of State Seward welcomed the withdrawal of concessions to the Confederates.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Finally, on October 18, Russell advised the Admiralty that the time specified in his June message had elapsed and "all measures of a restrictive nature on vessels of war of the United States in British ports, harbors, and waters, are now to be considered as at an end".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Nonetheless, the final Confederate surrender was in Liverpool, England where James Iredell Waddell, the captain of CSS *Shenandoah*, surrendered the cruiser to British authorities on November 6.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Legally, the war did not end until August 20, 1866, when President Johnson issued a proclamation that declared "that the said insurrection is at an end and that peace, order, tranquillity, and civil authority now exist in and throughout the whole of the United States of America".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The causes of the war, reasons for its outcome, and even its name are subjects of lingering contention.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The North and West grew wealthy while the once-rich South became poor for a century.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The national political power of the slaveowners and rich Southerners ended.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Historians are less sure about the results of postwar Reconstruction, especially regarding the second-class citizenship of the freedmen and their poverty.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Historians have debated whether the Confederacy could have won the war.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson, argue Confederate victory was possible.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson argues that the North's advantage in population and resources made Northern victory likely, but not guaranteed.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] He argues that if the Confederacy had fought using unconventional tactics, it would have more easily been able to hold out long enough to exhaust the Union.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Confederates did not need to invade and hold enemy territory to win, but only to fight a defensive war to convince the North the cost of winning was too high.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The North needed to conquer and hold vast stretches of enemy territory and defeat Confederate armies to win.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln was not a military dictator and could fight only as long as the American public supported the war.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederacy sought to win independence by outlasting Lincoln; however, after Atlanta fell and Lincoln defeated McClellan in the election of 1864, hope for a political victory for the South ended.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln had secured the support of the Republicans, War Democrats, border states, emancipated slaves, and the neutrality of Britain and France.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] By defeating the Democrats and McClellan, he defeated the Copperheads, who had wanted a negotiated peace with the Confederacy.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Some scholars argue the Union held an insurmountable long-term advantage over the Confederacy in industrial strength and population.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate actions, they argue, only delayed defeat.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] A minority view among historians is that the Confederacy lost because, as E.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Merton Coulter put it, "people did not will hard enough and long enough to win".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] However, most historians reject the argument.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson, after reading thousands of letters written by Confederate soldiers, found strong patriotism that continued to the end; they truly believed they were fighting for freedom and liberty.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Even as the Confederacy was visibly collapsing in 1864–65, most Confederate soldiers were fighting hard.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Also important were Lincoln's eloquence in articulating the national purpose and his skill in keeping the border states committed to the Union cause.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation was an effective use of the president's war powers.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederate government failed to get Europe involved militarily.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Southern leaders needed to get European powers to help break the blockade the Union had created around Southern ports.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's naval blockade was 95 percent effective at stopping trade goods; as a result, imports and exports to the South declined significantly.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The abundance of European cotton and Britain's hostility to slavery, along with Lincoln's naval blockades, severely decreased any chance that Britain or France would enter the war.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Doyle has argued that the Union victory had a major impact on world history.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Union victory energized popular democratic forces.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] A Confederate victory, on the other hand, would have meant a new birth of slavery, not of freedom.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Scholars have debated what the effects of the war were on political and economic power in the South.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The prevailing view is that the southern planter elite retained its powerful position in the South.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] However, a 2017 study challenges this, noting that while some Southern elites retained their economic status, the turmoil of the 1860s created greater opportunities for economic mobility in the South, than in the North.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Exact casualty figures were collected for the Union, but Confederate records were poorly kept, or lost in the chaos of defeat.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Thus, the casualty figures are imprecise and based on statistical extrapolation.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Neither side kept a tally of civilian deaths due to the war.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] In the 19th century, the death toll had been estimated at a lower 620,000.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] In 2011, the death toll was recalculated based on a 1% sample of census data, yielding approximately 750,000 soldier deaths, 20 percent higher than traditionally estimated, and possibly as high as 850,000.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The figure was recalculated to 698,000 soldier deaths in 2024 after examining newly available full census records.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Mortality rates among men were as high as 19 percent in Louisiana, and 16.6–16.7 percent in Georgia and South Carolina respectively.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The war resulted in at least 1,030,000 casualties (3 percent of the population), including an estimated 698,000 soldier deaths—two-thirds by disease.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Based on 1860 census figures, 8 percent of all white men aged 13–43 died in the war, including 6 percent in the North and 18 percent in the South.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] About 56,000 soldiers died in prison camps during the War.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] An estimated 60,000 soldiers lost limbs.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] As McPherson notes, the war's "cost in American lives was as great as in all of the nation's other wars combined through Vietnam".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] In addition, there were 4,523 deaths in the Navy (2,112 in battle) and 460 in the Marines (148 in battle).
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The US Colored Troops made up 10 percent of the Union death toll—15 percent of Union deaths from disease and less than 3 percent of those killed in battle.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Losses among African Americans were high.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] In the last year and a half and from all reported casualties, approximately 20 percent of all African Americans enrolled in the military died during the war.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Their mortality rate was significantly higher than white soldiers.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] While 15 percent of US Volunteers and just 9 percent of white Regular Army troops died, 21 percent of US Colored Troops died.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] While the figures of 360,000 army deaths for the Union and 260,000 for the Confederacy remained commonly cited, they are incomplete.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] This often happened only days or weeks later.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Francis Amasa Walker, superintendent of the 1870 census, used census and surgeon general data to estimate a minimum of 500,000 Union military deaths and 350,000 Confederate military deaths, a total of 850,000 soldiers.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] While Walker's estimates were originally dismissed because of the 1870 census's undercounting, it was later found that the census was only off by 6.5 percent and that the data Walker used would be roughly accurate.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Losses were far higher than during the war with Mexico, which saw roughly 13,000 American deaths, including fewer than two thousand killed in battle, between 1846 and 1848.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] One reason for the high number of battle deaths in the civil war was the continued use of tactics similar to those of the Napoleonic Wars, such as charging.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] With the advent of more accurate rifled barrels, Minié balls, and (near the end of the war for the Union) repeating firearms such as the Spencer repeating rifle and the Henry repeating rifle, soldiers were mowed down when standing in lines in the open.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] This led to the adoption of trench warfare, a style of fighting that defined much of World War I.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Deaths among former slaves has proven hard to estimate, due to the lack of reliable census data, though they were known to be considerable, as former slaves were set free or escaped in massive numbers in areas where the Union army did not have sufficient shelter, doctors, or food for them.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Professor Jim Downs states that tens of thousands to hundreds of thousands of slaves died during the war from disease, starvation, or exposure, and that if these deaths are counted in the war's total, the death toll would exceed 1 million.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] It is estimated that during the war, of the equines killed, including horses, mules, donkeys and even confiscated children's ponies, over 32,600 of them belonged to the Union and 45,800 the Confederacy.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] However, other estimates place the total at 1,000,000.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] It is estimated that 544 Confederate flags were captured during the war by the Union.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The flags were sent to the War Department in Washington.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Union flags captured by the Confederates were sent to Richmond.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Abolishing slavery was not a Union war goal from the outset but quickly became one.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln initially claimed that preserving the Union was the central goal.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] In contrast, the South fought to preserve slavery.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] While not all Southerners saw themselves as fighting for slavery, most officers and over a third of the rank and file in Lee's army had close family ties to slavery.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] To Northerners, the motivation was primarily to preserve the Union, not to abolish slavery.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's decision to issue the Proclamation angered Peace Democrats ("Copperheads") and War Democrats, but energized most Republicans.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] By warning that free blacks would flood the North, Democrats made gains in the 1862 elections, but they did not gain control of Congress.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Republicans' counterargument that slavery was the mainstay of the enemy steadily gained support, with the Democrats losing decisively in the 1863 elections in the Northern state of Ohio, when they tried to resurrect anti-black sentiment.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation legally freed the slaves in states "in rebellion", but, as a practical matter, slavery for the 3.5 million black people in the South effectively ended in each area when Union armies arrived.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The last Confederate slaves were freed on June 19, 1865, celebrated as the modern holiday of Juneteenth.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Slaves in the border states and those in some former Confederate territory occupied before the Emancipation Proclamation were freed by state action or (on December 6, 1865) by the Thirteenth Amendment.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation enabled African Americans, both free blacks and escaped slaves, to join the Union Army.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] About 190,000 volunteered, further enhancing the numerical advantage the Union armies enjoyed over the Confederates, who did not dare emulate the equivalent manpower source for fear of undermining the legitimacy of slavery.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] During the war, sentiment concerning slaves, enslavement, and emancipation in the United States was divided.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's fears of making slavery a war issue were based on a harsh reality: abolition did not enjoy wide support in the west, the territories, and the border states.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] In 1861, Lincoln worried that premature attempts at emancipation would mean the loss of the border states, and that "to lose Kentucky is nearly the same as to lose the whole game".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Copperheads and some War Democrats opposed emancipation, although the latter eventually accepted it as part of the total war needed to save the Union.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln reversed attempts at emancipation by Secretary of War Simon Cameron and Generals John C.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Frémont and David Hunter, in an effort to retain the loyalty of the border states and the War Democrats.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln warned the border states that a more radical type of emancipation would happen if they rejected his plan of gradual compensated emancipation and voluntary colonization.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] But compensated emancipation occurred only in the District of Columbia, where Congress had the power to enact it.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] When Lincoln told his cabinet about his proposed emancipation proclamation, which would apply to the states still in rebellion on January 1, 1863, Seward advised Lincoln to wait for a Union military victory before issuing it, because to do otherwise would seem like "our last shriek on the retreat".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Walter Stahr, however, writes, "There are contemporary sources, however, that suggest others were involved in the decision to delay", and Stahr quotes them.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] , who were fugitive slaves, including cooks, laundresses, laborers, teamsters, railroad repair crews, fled to the Union Army, but were not legally freed until the Emancipation Proclamation, which Lincoln signed on January 1, 1863, more than two years before the end of the Civil War.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] ; seen here are black and white teenaged soldiers who volunteered to fight for the Union.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln laid the groundwork for public support in an open letter published in response to Horace Greeley's "The Prayer of Twenty Millions"; the letter stated that Lincoln's goal was to save the Union, and that, if he freed the slaves, it would be as a means to that end.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] He also had a meeting at the White House with five African American representatives on August 14, 1862.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Arranging for a reporter to be present, he urged his visitors to agree to the voluntary colonization of black people.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's motive for both his letter to Greeley and his statement to the black visitors was apparently to make his forthcoming Emancipation Proclamation more palatable to racist white people.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] A Union victory in the Battle of Antietam on September 17, 1862, provided Lincoln with an opportunity to issue the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation, and the War Governors' Conference added support for the proclamation.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln issued his preliminary Emancipation Proclamation on September 22, 1862.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] It stated that slaves in all states in rebellion on January 1, 1863, would be free.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] He issued his final Emancipation Proclamation on January 1, 1863, keeping his promise.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Hodges, Lincoln explained his belief that "If slavery is not wrong, nothing is wrong....
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] And yet I have never understood that the Presidency conferred upon me an unrestricted right to act officially upon this judgment and feeling....
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's moderate approach succeeded in inducing the border states to remain in the Union and War Democrats to support the Union.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The border states, which included Kentucky, Missouri, Maryland, Delaware, and Union-controlled regions around New Orleans, Norfolk, Virginia, and elsewhere, were not covered by the Emancipation Proclamation.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Nor was Tennessee, which had come under Union control.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Missouri and Maryland abolished slavery on their own; Kentucky and Delaware did not.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Still, the proclamation did not enjoy universal support.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] It caused much unrest in what were then considered western states, where racist sentiments led to a great fear of abolition.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] There was some concern that the proclamation would lead to the secession of western states, and its issuance prompted the stationing of Union troops in Illinois in case of rebellion.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] Since the Emancipation Proclamation was based on the president's war powers, it applied only in territory held by Confederates at the time it was issued.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] However, the Proclamation became a symbol of the Union's growing commitment to add emancipation to the Union's definition of liberty.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation greatly reduced the Confederacy's hope of being recognized or otherwise aided by Britain or France.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p02] By late 1864, Lincoln was playing a leading role in getting the House of Representatives to vote for the Thirteenth Amendment, which mandated the ending of chattel slavery.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] The war devastated the South and posed serious questions of how it would be reintegrated into the Union.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] The war destroyed much of the South's wealth, in part because wealth held in enslaved people (at least $1,000 each for a healthy adult prior to the war) was wiped off the books.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] All accumulated investment in Confederate bonds was forfeited; most banks and railroads were bankrupt.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] The income per person dropped to less than 40 percent of that of the North, and that lasted into the 20th century.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] Southern influence in the federal government, previously considerable, was greatly diminished until the second half of the 20th century.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] Reconstruction began during the war, with the Emancipation Proclamation of January 1863, and it continued until 1877.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] From the Union perspective, the goals of Reconstruction were to consolidate victory by reuniting the Union, to guarantee a "republican form of government" for the ex-Confederate states, and to permanently end slavery—and prevent semi-slavery status.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] President Johnson, who took office in April 1865, took a lenient approach and saw the achievement of the main war goals as realized in 1865, when each ex-rebel state repudiated secession and ratified the Thirteenth Amendment.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] Radical Republicans demanded proof that Confederate nationalism was dead and that the slaves were truly free.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] They overrode Johnson's vetoes of civil rights legislation, and the House impeached him, although the Senate did not convict him.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] In 1868 and 1872, the Republican candidate Grant won the presidency.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] In 1872, the "Liberal Republicans" argued that the war goals had been achieved and Reconstruction should end.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] They chose Horace Greeley to head a presidential ticket in 1872 but were decisively defeated.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] In 1874, Democrats, primarily Southern, took control of Congress and opposed further reconstruction.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] The Compromise of 1877 closed with a national consensus, except on the part of former slaves, that the war had finally ended.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] With the withdrawal of federal troops, however, white men retook control of every Southern legislature, and the Jim Crow era of disenfranchisement and legal segregation was ushered in.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] The war had a demonstrable impact on American politics.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] Many veterans on both sides were elected to political office, including five US presidents: Ulysses Grant, Rutherford B.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] Garfield, Benjamin Harrison, and William McKinley.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] The war is a central event in American collective memory.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] There are innumerable statues, commemorations, books, and archival collections.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] The memory includes the home front, military affairs, the treatment of soldiers, both living and dead, in the war's aftermath, depictions of the war in literature and art, evaluations of heroes and villains, and considerations of the moral and political lessons of the war.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] The last theme includes moral evaluations of racism and slavery, heroism and cowardice in combat and behind the lines, and issues of democracy and minority rights, as well as the notion of an "Empire of Liberty" influencing the world.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] Historians have paid great attention to the causes of the war as well as to the war itself.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] Military history has developed outside as well as inside academia, leading to a proliferation of studies by non-scholars who nevertheless are familiar with the primary sources and pay close attention to battles and campaigns and who write for the general public.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] Practically every major figure in the war, both North and South, has had a serious biographical study.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] Even the name used for the conflict has been controversial, with many names used for it.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] During and immediately after the war, Northern historians often used a term like "War of the Rebellion".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] Writers in rebel states often referred to the "War for Southern Independence".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] Some Southerners have described it as the "War of Northern Aggression".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] The memory of the war in the white South crystallized in the myth of the "Lost Cause": that the Confederate cause was just and heroic.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] The myth shaped regional identity and race relations for generations.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] Nolan notes that the Lost Cause was expressly a rationalization, a cover-up to vindicate the name and fame of those in rebellion.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] Some claims revolve around the insignificance of slavery as a cause; some appeals highlight cultural differences between North and South; the military conflict by Confederate actors is idealized; in any case, secession was said to be lawful.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] Nolan argues that the adoption of the Lost Cause perspective facilitated the reunification of the North and the South while excusing the "virulent racism" of the 19th century, sacrificing black American progress to white man's reunification.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] He also deems the Lost Cause "a caricature of the truth.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] This caricature wholly misrepresents and distorts the facts of the matter" in every instance.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] The Lost Cause myth was formalized by Charles A.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] Beard, whose *The Rise of American Civilization* (1927) spawned Beardian historiography.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] The Beards downplayed slavery, abolitionism, and issues of morality.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] Though this interpretation was abandoned by the Beards in the 1940s, and by historians generally by the 1950s, Beardian themes still echo among Lost Cause writers.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] The first efforts at Civil War battlefield preservation and memorialization came during the war, with the establishment of National Cemeteries at Gettysburg, Mill Springs and Chattanooga.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] Soldiers began erecting markers on battlefields beginning with the First Battle of Bull Run in 1861.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] The oldest surviving monument is the Hazen Brigade Monument near Murfreesboro in Central Tennessee, built in the summer of 1863 by soldiers in Union Col.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] Hazen's brigade to mark the spot where they buried their dead, following the Battle of Stones River.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] The Shiloh National Military Park was established in 1894 in Shiloh, Tennessee, followed by the Gettysburg National Military Park in 1895, and Vicksburg National Military Park in 1899.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] In 1933, these five parks and other national monuments were transferred to the National Park Service.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] Chief among modern efforts to preserve Civil War sites has been the American Battlefield Trust, with more than 130 battlefields in 24 states.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] The five major battlefield parks operated by the National Park Service had a combined 3 million visitors in 2018, down 70% from 10 million in 1970.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] The Civil War has been commemorated in many ways, ranging from the reenactment of battles, to statues and memorial halls being erected, to films, and to stamps and coins with Civil War themes being issued, all of which helped to shape public memory.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] These commemorations occurred in greater numbers on the 100th and 150th anniversaries of the war.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] Hollywood's take on the war has been especially influential in shaping public memory, as in such film classics as *The Birth of a Nation* (1915), *Gone with the Wind* (1939), and *Lincoln* (2012).
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] Ken Burns's PBS television series *The Civil War* (1990) is well-remembered, though criticized for its historical inaccuracy.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] Technological innovations during the war had a great impact on 19th-century science.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] The war was an early example of an "industrial war", in which technological might is used to achieve military supremacy.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] New inventions, such as the train and telegraph, delivered soldiers, supplies and messages at a time when horses had been the fastest way to travel.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] It was also in this war that aerial warfare, in the form of reconnaissance balloons, was first used.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] It saw the first action involving steam-powered ironclad warships in naval warfare history.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] Repeating firearms such as the Henry rifle, Spencer repeating rifle, Colt revolving rifle, Triplett & Scott carbine and others, first appeared during the Civil War; they were a revolutionary invention that would soon replace muzzle-loading and single-shot firearms.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] The war saw the first appearances of rapid-firing weapons and machine guns such as the Agar gun and Gatling gun.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] The Civil War is one of the most studied events in American history, and the collection of cultural works around it is enormous.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/american-civil-war-p03] This section gives an abbreviated overview of the most notable works.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/commercial-street-portland-maine] Built upon old piers in the 1850s, fill was pushed into Casco Bay to accommodate the growing Portland Terminal Company railroad and warehousing needs of the port's working waterfront.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/commercial-street-portland-maine] In the 1970s and 1980s, much of the economic activity on the street was hurt and many of the properties on the street were sold off for non-marine development, including the building of condominiums.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/commercial-street-portland-maine] In 1987, Portland voters, led by local fisherman based on Commercial Street, halted all non-marine development along the street and adjacent docks.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/commercial-street-portland-maine] Marine development around Commercial Street returned in the 1990s and 2000s (decade) alongside other economic development, including tourism-related industries.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/commercial-street-portland-maine] The Maine State Pier, a deepwater marine facility and outdoor music venue, is located at the intersection of Commercial Street and Franklin Street.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/commercial-street-portland-maine] The former Portland Star Match Factory is located at 65–89 West Commercial Street, near the West End.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/commercial-street-portland-maine] Jordan's Ready to Eat Meats formerly occupied the northwestern corner of Silver Street and Commercial Street.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/commercial-street-portland-maine] It moved to Fore Street and India Street in the early 1960s.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/commercial-street-portland-maine] The street, which was originally known as Thames Street, becomes West Commercial Street from beneath the Casco Bay Bridge heading west.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/commercial-street-portland-maine] Thames Street still exists from India Street heading northeast, eventually merging into footpaths beneath the Eastern Promenade.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/commercial-street-portland-maine] In 2008, it was named one of the ten best streets in the United States by the American Planning Association.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/commercial-street-portland-maine] The below sixteen wharves and piers are located along Commercial Street.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/commercial-street-portland-maine] By the time of Commercial Street's completion in 1853, four of today's remaining wharves (Chandler's, Union, Merrill's and Berlin Mills) had built tracks to Commercial Street to improve trade opportunities.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/commercial-street-portland-maine] Three wharves (Richardson's, Brown's and Smith's) were demolished with the creation of the City of Portland Fish Pier at the foot of Center Street.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Fire, in its most common form, has the potential to result in conflagration, which can lead to permanent physical damage.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Fire directly affects land-based ecological systems worldwide.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The benefits of fire include stimulating plant growth and maintaining ecological balance.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Its harms include hazards to life and property, atmospheric pollution, and water contamination.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] When fire removes protective vegetation, heavy rainfall can cause soil erosion.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The burning of vegetation releases nitrogen into the atmosphere, unlike other plant nutrients such as potassium and phosphorus, which remain in the ash and are quickly recycled into the soil.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] This loss of nitrogen produces a long-term reduction in the fertility of the soil.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] However, it can be recovered by *nitrogen-fixing* plants—some of them of agricultural value, such as clover, peas, and beans, by decomposition of animal waste and corpses, and by natural phenomena such as lightning.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Various technologies and strategies have been devised to prevent, manage, mitigate, and extinguish fires, with professional firefighters playing a leading role.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] For example, most home fires start from unattended cooking, although cigarettes are another major cause.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Smoke detectors and sprinkler systems greatly reduce harm from home fires.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The word *fire* comes from Old English *fȳr* and has cognates in many Germanic languages and other Indo-European languages.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The Proto-Germanic nominative form is reconstructed as **fōr*, descending from Proto-Indo-European **péh2wr*.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] An alternative spelling existed in Middle English: *fier*; still preserved in *fiery*.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The word *ignite* is derived from the classical Latin *ignis* meaning fire.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The Greek term for fire, *pyr*, is used in words such as pyroclastic or pyrotechnic.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The fossil record of fire first appears with the establishment of a land-based flora in the Middle Ordovician period, 470 million years ago.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] These land plants contributed large amounts of oxygen to the atmosphere when they released it as a waste product.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] When this concentration rose above 13%, it made a wildfire possible.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Wildfire is first recorded in the Late Silurian fossil record, 420 million years ago, by fossils of charred plants.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Apart from a controversial gap in the Late Devonian, charcoal is present ever since.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The level of atmospheric oxygen is closely correlated with the amount of charcoal in the fossil record, clearly pointing to oxygen as the key factor in the prevalence of wildfire.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Fire also became more abundant when grasses became the dominant component of many ecosystems, around 6 to 7 million years ago, providing excellent tinder for more rapid spread of fire.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] This widespread emergence of wildfire may have initiated a positive feedback process, whereby they produced a warmer, drier climate more conducive to fire.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Fire made it possible for humans to live in colder places and dark caves.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] It also protected humans against dangerous animals.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] It caused nutritional changes, and it enabled people to eat with more variety.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The period of history characterized by the influence of human-caused fire activity on Earth has been dubbed the pyrocene.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] This epoch includes the burning of fossil fuels, especially for technological uses.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The ability to control fire was a dramatic change in the habits of early humans.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Making fire to generate heat and light made it possible for people to cook food, simultaneously increasing the variety and availability of nutrients and reducing disease by killing pathogenic microorganisms in the food.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The heat produced would also help people stay warm in cold weather, enabling them to live in cooler climates.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Fire also kept nocturnal predators at bay.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Evidence of occasional cooked food is found from 1 million years ago, suggesting it was used in a controlled fashion.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Other sources put the date of regular use at 400,000 years ago.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Evidence becomes widespread around 50 to 100 thousand years ago, suggesting regular use from this time; resistance to air pollution started to evolve in human populations at a similar point in time.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The use of fire became progressively more sophisticated, as it was used to create charcoal and to control wildlife from tens of thousands of years ago.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] By the Neolithic Revolution, during the introduction of grain-based agriculture, people all over the world used fire as a tool in landscape management.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] These fires were typically controlled burns or "cool fires", as opposed to uncontrolled "hot fires", which damage the soil.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Hot fires destroy plants and animals and endanger communities.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] This is especially a problem in the forests of today where traditional burning is prevented to encourage the growth of timber crops.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Cool fires are generally conducted in the spring and autumn.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] They clear undergrowth, burning up biomass that could trigger a hot fire should it get too dense.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] They provide a greater variety of environments, which encourages game and plant diversity.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Humans make dense, impassable forests traversable.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Another human use of fire in landscape management is to clear land for agriculture.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Slash-and-burn agriculture is still common across much of tropical Africa, Asia, and South America.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] For small farmers, controlled fires are a convenient way to clear overgrown areas and release nutrients from standing vegetation back into the soil.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] However, this useful strategy is also problematic.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] A growing population, forest fragmentation, and a warming climate are making the Earth's surface more prone to ever-larger escaped fires.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] These harm ecosystems and human infrastructure, cause health problems, and send spirals of carbon and soot into the atmosphere that may encourage even more warming – and thus feed back into more fires.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Globally today, as much as 5 million square kilometres – an area more than half the size of the United States – burns in a given year.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Throughout much of history, cultures attempted to explain nature and the properties of matter by proposing a set of four (or five) classical elements, of which fire was one of the components.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] As scientific understanding developed following the Middle Ages, this philosophy was replaced by a set of chemical elements and their interactions.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Instead, the classical elements found an equivalency in the states of matter: solid, liquid, gas, and plasma.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] During the 17th century, a study of combustion was made by Jan Baptist van Helmont who discovered that burning charcoal released a *gas sylvestris*, or wild spirit.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] This was subsequently incorporated into Phlogiston theory by Johann Joachim Becher in 1667 and more formally by Georg Ernst Stahl in 1697; a concept that would strongly influence alchemical thinking for nearly two centuries.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] It was Antoine Lavoisier who demonstrated that combustion did not involve the release of a substance, but rather something was being taken up.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] In 1777, Lavoisier proposed a new theory of combustion based on the reaction of a material with a component of air, which he termed oxygène.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] By 1791, Lavoisier's chemical concepts had been widely adopted by young scientists, and the Phlogiston theory had been rejected.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Fire has been used for centuries as a method of torture and execution, as evidenced by death by burning as well as torture devices such as the iron boot, which could be heated over an open fire to the agony of the wearer.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] There are numerous modern applications of fire.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] In its broadest sense, fire is used by nearly every human being on Earth in a controlled setting every day.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Users of internal combustion vehicles employ fire every time they drive.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Thermal power stations provide electricity for a large percentage of humanity by igniting fuels such as coal, oil or natural gas, then using the resultant heat to boil water into steam, which then drives turbines.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The use of fire in warfare has a long history.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Fire was the basis of all early thermal weapons, including incendiary devices, heated projectiles, and the use of smoke.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] This class of weapons was particularly evident during naval battles and siege warfare.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The Byzantine fleet used Greek fire to attack ships and men.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The invention of gunpowder in China led to the fire lance, a flame-thrower dating to around 1000 CE, a precursor to projectile weapons driven by burning gunpowder.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The earliest modern flamethrowers were used by infantry in the First World War, first used by German troops against entrenched French troops near Verdun in February 1915.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] They were later successfully mounted on armoured vehicles in the Second World War.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Hand-thrown incendiary bombs improvised from glass bottles, later known as Molotov cocktails, were deployed during the Spanish Civil War in the 1930s.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] During that war, incendiary bombs were deployed against Guernica by Fascist Italian and Nazi German air forces that had been created specifically to support Franco's Nationalists.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Incendiary bombs were dropped by Axis and Allies during the Second World War, notably on Coventry, Tokyo, Rotterdam, London, Hamburg and Dresden.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] In the latter two cases, firestorms were deliberately caused, in which a ring of fire surrounding each city was drawn inward by an updraft created by a central cluster of fires.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The United States Army Air Force extensively used incendiaries against Japanese targets in the latter months of the war, devastating entire cities constructed primarily of wood and paper houses.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The incendiary fluid napalm was used in July 1944, towards the end of the Second World War, although its use did not gain public attention until the Vietnam War.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Burning fuel converts chemical energy into heat energy; wood has been used as fuel since prehistory.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The International Energy Agency states that nearly 80% of the world's power has consistently come from fossil fuels such as petroleum, natural gas, and coal in the past decades.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The fire in a power station is used to heat water, creating steam that drives turbines.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The turbines then spin an electric generator to produce electricity.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Fire is also used to provide mechanical work directly by thermal expansion, in both external and internal combustion engines.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The unburnable solid remains of a combustible material left after a fire is called *clinker* if its melting point is below the flame temperature, so that it fuses and then solidifies as it cools, and *ash* if its melting point is above the flame temperature.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Fire is a chemical process in which a fuel and an oxidizing agent react, yielding carbon dioxide and water.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] This process, known as a combustion reaction, does not proceed directly and involves intermediates.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Although the oxidizing agent is typically oxygen, other compounds can fulfill the role.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] For instance, chlorine trifluoride is able to ignite sand.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] This is commonly called the fire tetrahedron.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Fire cannot exist without all of these elements in place and in the right proportions.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] For example, a flammable liquid will start burning only if the fuel and oxygen are in the right proportions.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Some fuel-oxygen mixes may require a catalyst, a substance that is not consumed, when added, in any chemical reaction during combustion, but which enables the reactants to combust more readily.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Once ignited, a chain reaction occurs whereby fires can sustain their own heat through the continued release of heat energy during combustion and may propagate, provided there is a continuous supply of an oxidizer and fuel.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] If the oxidizer is oxygen from the surrounding air, the presence of a force of gravity, or of some similar force caused by acceleration, is necessary to produce convection, which removes combustion products and brings a supply of oxygen to the fire.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Without gravity, a fire rapidly surrounds itself with its own combustion products and non-oxidizing gases from the air, which exclude oxygen and extinguish the fire.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Because of this, the risk of fire in a spacecraft is small when it is coasting in inertial flight.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] This does not apply if oxygen is supplied to the fire by some process other than thermal convection.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Fire can be extinguished by removing any one of the elements of the fire tetrahedron.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Consider a natural gas flame, such as from a stove-top burner.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] In contrast, fire is intensified by increasing the overall combustion rate.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] A diffusion flame is a mixture of reacting gases and solids emitting visible, infrared, and sometimes ultraviolet light, the frequency spectrum of which depends on the chemical composition of the burning material and intermediate reaction products.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] During the burning of hydrocarbons, for example wood, or the incomplete combustion of gas, incandescent solid particles called soot produce the familiar red-orange glow of "fire".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Complete combustion of gas has a dim blue color due to the emission of single-wavelength radiation from various electron transitions in the excited molecules formed in the flame.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Usually oxygen is involved, but hydrogen burning in chlorine also produces a flame, producing hydrogen chloride (HCl).
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Other possible combinations producing flames, amongst many, are fluorine with hydrogen, and hydrazine with dinitrogen tetroxide.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Hydrogen and hydrazine/UDMH flames are similarly pale blue, while burning boron and its compounds, evaluated in mid-20th century as a high energy fuel for jet and rocket engines, emits intense green flame, leading to its informal nickname of "Green Dragon".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Black-body radiation is emitted from soot, gas, and fuel particles, though the soot particles are too small to behave like perfect blackbodies.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] There is also photon emission by de-excited atoms and molecules in the gases.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Much of the radiation is emitted in the visible and infrared bands.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The color depends on temperature for the black-body radiation, and on chemical makeup for the emission spectra.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The common distribution of a flame under normal gravity conditions depends on convection, as soot tends to rise to the top of a general flame, as in a candle in normal gravity conditions, making it yellow.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] There are several possible explanations for this difference, the most likely being that the temperature is sufficiently uniform that soot does not form and complete combustion occurs.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Experiments by NASA reveal that diffusion flames in microgravity allow more soot to be completely oxidized after they are produced than diffusion flames on Earth, because of a series of mechanisms that behave differently in micro gravity when compared to normal gravity conditions.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] These discoveries have potential applications in applied science and industry, especially concerning fuel efficiency.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The adiabatic flame temperature of a given fuel-oxidizer pair is the temperature at which the gases achieve stable combustion.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Fire science is a branch of physical science which includes fire behavior, dynamics, and combustion.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Applications of fire science include fire protection, fire investigation, and wildfire management.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Every natural ecosystem on land has its own fire regime, and the organisms in those ecosystems are adapted to or dependent upon that fire regime.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Fire creates a mosaic of different habitat patches, each at a different stage of succession.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Different species of plants, animals, and microbes specialize in exploiting a particular stage, and by creating these different types of patches, fire allows a greater number of species to exist within a landscape.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Changes in climate can significantly modify the risk for wildfires in a region.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Fire fighting services are provided in most developed areas to extinguish or contain uncontrolled fires.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Trained firefighters use fire apparatus, water supply resources such as water mains and fire hydrants, or they might use A and B class foam depending on what is feeding the fire.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The early detection of a wildfire outbreak can be performed by a fire lookout observing from a tower constructed for that purpose.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The use of these towers peaked in 1938 and has been in decline since then; most fire surveillance work is now performed using infrared sensors and aircraft.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Fire suppression aircraft guided by a lookout can be used to help manage wildfires.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Controlling a fire to optimize its size, shape, and intensity is generally called *fire management*, and the more advanced forms of it, as traditionally (and sometimes still) practiced by skilled cooks, blacksmiths, ironmasters, and others, are highly skilled activities.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Detailed expositions of fire management are available in various books on blacksmithing, skilled camping or military scouting, and domestic arts.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Wildfire prevention programs around the world may employ techniques such as *wildland fire use* and *prescribed or controlled burns*.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] *Wildland fire use* refers to any fire of natural causes that is monitored but allowed to burn.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] *Controlled burns* are fires ignited by government agencies under less dangerous weather conditions.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Fire prevention is intended to reduce sources of ignition.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Fire prevention also includes education on how to avoid causing fires.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Buildings, especially schools and tall buildings, often conduct fire drills to inform and prepare citizens on how to react to a building fire.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Purposely starting destructive fires constitutes arson and is a crime in most jurisdictions.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Model building codes require passive fire protection and active fire protection systems to minimize damage resulting from a fire.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] A common form of active fire protection is fire sprinklers.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] To maximize passive fire protection of buildings, building materials and furnishings in most developed countries are tested for fire-resistance, combustibility and flammability.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Upholstery, carpeting and plastics used in vehicles and vessels are also tested.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Studies have found that functioning smoke detectors reduce the risk of death in a fire by 50%, and sprinkler systems can reduce mortality by 100%.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Fire-resistant clothing, beds, and sofas have also been shown to reduce injuries resulting from fires.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] In the United States, the leading cause of residential fires is cooking equipment, particularly cooking left unattended.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] It is estimated that cigarettes and other smoking materials are responsible for about 28% of home fires involving the ignition of upholstered furniture, and for approximately 58% of the fatalities in such fires.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Fires started by cigarettes are also more lethal and have higher mortality rates than fires that spread from open flames.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The adoption of fire-safe cigarettes has been associated with a 45% reduction in fires caused by cigarettes.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Where fire prevention and fire protection have failed to prevent damage, fire insurance can mitigate the financial impact.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Fire has been an importance element of human culture since the Lower Paleolithic.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Archaeological evidence demonstrates that fire worship has been widely practiced since prehistory, with dedicated structures found dating from at least the Chalcolithic period.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The religion of Zoroastrianism is closely linked to this practice.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] In some societies fire was a deity, while others viewed it as the manifestation of the divine.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The fire in a hearth was perceived as symbolic of the Heavenly Fire, and thus is considered a sacred component by fire-worshipping cultures.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The origin of fire became a subject of mythology.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] In ancient Greek culture, the Titan god Prometheus was responsible for stealing heavenly fire and giving it to humanity.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The use of a pyre as a funerary practice dates back to at least the Ancient Roman period in the West, and to about 4,000 years ago on the Indian subcontinent.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Cremation of corpses is a tradition long practiced in some cultures, including Hindu.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] After early religious resistance in some countries, in the 19th century this practice became more widespread and is now commonplace.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] In some nations, suicide by self-immolation remains common.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The symbology of fire remains important to the present day.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Where wood is plentiful, the bonfire can be used for celebration purposes, in many cases as part of a tradition.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] An example is Guy Fawkes Night in England.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The barbecue is a fire-based cultural tradition in the United States.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The fiery ignition of fireworks has become a modern tradition to celebrate the New Year's arrival.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] In contrast, book burning has been used as a form of protest, whether for political, religious, or moral reasons.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] The act of "burning in effigy" has a similar role, as in the annual burning of Judas ritual.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Humans lack an instinctual fascination with fire, yet in modern societies, adults can become drawn to it out of curiosity.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] In societies that rely on daily fire use, children lose interest in fire around age 7 due to regular exposure.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] Arson is the act of intentionally setting fire to a property.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] A separate but related behavior is pyromania, which is classified as an impulse-control disorder where individuals repeatedly fail to resist impulses to start fires deliberately.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] In contrast is pyrophobia, an irrational fear of fire.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/fire] This anxiety disorder is a less common phobia.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] A **geographic coordinate system** (**GCS**) is a spherical or geodetic coordinate system for measuring and communicating positions directly on Earth as latitude and longitude.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] It is the simplest, oldest, and most widely used type of the various spatial reference systems that are in use, and forms the basis for most others.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] Although latitude and longitude form a coordinate tuple like a Cartesian coordinate system, geographic coordinate systems are not Cartesian because the measurements are angles and are not on a planar surface.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] A full GCS specification, such as those listed in the EPSG and ISO 19111 standards, also includes a choice of geodetic datum (including an Earth ellipsoid), as different datums will yield different latitude and longitude values for the same location.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] The invention of a geographic coordinate system is generally credited to Eratosthenes of Cyrene, who composed his now-lost *Geography* at the Library of Alexandria in the 3rd century BC.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] A century later, Hipparchus of Nicaea improved on this system by determining latitude from stellar measurements rather than solar altitude and determining longitude by timings of lunar eclipses, rather than dead reckoning.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] Ptolemy credited him with the full adoption of longitude and latitude, rather than measuring latitude in terms of the length of the midsummer day.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] Ptolemy's 2nd-century *Geography* used the same prime meridian but measured latitude from the Equator instead.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] After their work was translated into Arabic in the 9th century, Al-Khwārizmī's *Book of the Description of the Earth* corrected Marinus' and Ptolemy's errors regarding the length of the Mediterranean Sea, causing medieval Arabic cartography to use a prime meridian around 10° east of Ptolemy's line.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] Mathematical cartography resumed in Europe following Maximus Planudes' recovery of Ptolemy's text a little before 1300; the text was translated into Latin at Florence by Jacopo d'Angelo around 1407.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] In 1884, the United States hosted the International Meridian Conference, attended by representatives from twenty-five nations.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] Twenty-two of them agreed to adopt the longitude of the Royal Observatory in Greenwich, England as the zero-reference line.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] The Dominican Republic voted against the motion, while France and Brazil abstained.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] France adopted Greenwich Mean Time in place of local determinations by the Paris Observatory in 1911.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] The *latitude* φ of a point on Earth's surface is defined in one of three ways, depending on the type of coordinate system.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] In each case, the latitude is the angle formed by the plane of the equator and a line formed by the point on the surface and a second point on equatorial plane.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] The path that joins all points of the same latitude traces a circle on the surface of Earth, as viewed from above the north or south pole, called parallels, as they are parallel to the equator and to each other.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] The north pole is 90° N; the south pole is 90° S.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] The 0° parallel of latitude is defined to be the equator, the fundamental plane of a geographic coordinate system.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] The equator divides the globe into Northern and Southern Hemispheres.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] The *longitude* λ of a point on Earth's surface is the angle east or west of a reference meridian to another meridian that passes through that point.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] All meridians are halves of great ellipses, which converge at the North and South Poles.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] The meridian of the British Royal Observatory in Greenwich, in southeast London, England, is the international prime meridian, although some organizations—such as the French Institut national de l'information géographique et forestière—continue to use other meridians for internal purposes.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] The antipodal meridian of Greenwich is both 180°W and 180°E.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] This is not to be conflated with the International Date Line, which partly overlaps with the 180° meridian but diverges from it in several places for political and convenience reasons, including between far eastern Russia and the far western Aleutian Islands.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] The combination of these two components specifies the position of any location on the surface of Earth, without consideration of altitude or depth.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] The visual grid on a map formed by lines of latitude and longitude is known as a *graticule*.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] The origin/zero point of this system is located in the Gulf of Guinea about 625 km (390 mi) south of Tema, Ghana, a location often facetiously called Null Island.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] In order to use the theoretical definitions of latitude, longitude, and height to precisely measure actual locations on the physical earth, a *geodetic datum* must be used.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] A *horizonal datum* is used to precisely measure latitude and longitude, while a *vertical datum* is used to measure elevation or altitude.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] Both types of datum bind a mathematical model of the shape of the earth (usually a reference ellipsoid for a horizontal datum, and a more precise geoid for a vertical datum) to the earth.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] Traditionally, this binding was created by a network of control points, surveyed locations at which monuments are installed, and were only accurate for a region of the surface of the Earth.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] Newer datums are based on a global network for satellite measurements (GNSS, VLBI, SLR and DORIS).
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] This combination of a mathematical model and physical binding ensures that users of the same datum obtain identical coordinates for a given physical point.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] However, different datums typically produce different coordinates for the same location (sometimes deviating several hundred meters) not due to actual movement, but because the reference system itself is shifted.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] Because any spatial reference system or map projection is ultimately calculated from latitude and longitude, it is crucial that they clearly state the datum on which they are based.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] For example, a UTM coordinate based on a WGS84 realisation will be different than a UTM coordinate based on NAD27 for the same location.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] Transforming coordinates from one datum to another requires a datum transformation method such as a Helmert transformation, although in certain situations a simple translation may be sufficient.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] Datums may be global, meaning that they represent the whole Earth, or they may be regional, meaning that they represent an ellipsoid best-fit to only a portion of the Earth.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] Datums with a regional fit of the ellipsoid that are chosen by a national cartographical organization include the North American Datums, the European ED50, and the British OSGB36.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] Given a location, the datum provides the latitude $\phi$ and longitude $\lambda$ .
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] In the United Kingdom there are three common latitude, longitude, and height systems in use.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] WGS 84 differs at Greenwich from the one used on published maps OSGB36 by approximately 112 m.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] Points on the Earth's surface move relative to each other due to continental plate motion, subsidence, and diurnal Earth tidal movement caused by the Moon and the Sun.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] This daily movement can be as much as a meter.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] Continental movement can be up to 10 cm a year, or 10 m in a century.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] A weather system high-pressure area can cause a sinking of 5 mm.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] Scandinavia is rising by 1 cm a year as a result of the melting of the ice sheets of the last ice age, but neighboring Scotland is rising by only 0.2 cm.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] These changes are insignificant if a regional datum is used, but are statistically significant if a global datum is used.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] On the GRS 80 or WGS 84 spheroid at sea level at the Equator, one latitudinal second measures 30.715 m, one latitudinal minute is 1843 m and one latitudinal degree is 110.6 km.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] The circles of longitude, meridians, meet at the geographical poles, with the west–east width of a second naturally decreasing as latitude increases.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] On the Equator at sea level, one longitudinal second measures 30.92 m, a longitudinal minute is 1855 m and a longitudinal degree is 111.3 km.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] The returned measure of meters per degree latitude varies continuously with latitude.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] The formulae both return units of meters per degree.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] ( $\textstyle {\beta }\,\!$ is known as the reduced (or parametric) latitude).
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] Aside from rounding, this is the exact distance along a parallel of latitude; getting the distance along the shortest route will be more work, but those two distances are always within 0.6 m of each other if the two points are one degree of longitude apart.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] Like any series of multiple-digit numbers, latitude-longitude pairs can be challenging to communicate and remember.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/geographic-coordinate-system] These are not distinct coordinate systems, only alternative methods for expressing latitude and longitude measurements.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] The **Great Chicago Fire** was a conflagration that burned in Chicago, Illinois, United States, during October 8–10, 1871.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] The fire killed approximately 300 people, destroyed 17,000 structures across roughly 3.3 square miles (9 km2), and left more than 100,000 residents homeless.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] The fire began in a neighborhood southwest of the city center.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] A long period of hot, dry, windy conditions, and the wooden construction prevalent in the city, led to the conflagration spreading quickly.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] The fire leapt the south branch of the Chicago River and destroyed much of central Chicago and then crossed the main stem of the river, consuming the Near North Side.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Help flowed to the city from near and far after the fire.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] The city government improved building codes to stop the rapid spread of future fires and rebuilt rapidly to those higher standards.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] A donation from the United Kingdom spurred the establishment of the Chicago Public Library.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] According to Nancy Connolly, great-great-granddaughter of Catherine O'Leary, the fire is said to have started at about 8:30 p.m. on October 8, in or around a small barn belonging to the O'Leary family that bordered the alley behind 137 W.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] DeKoven Street when Daniel "Peg-Leg" Sullivan accidentally knocked over a lantern while looking for beer for a party.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] The shed next to the barn was the first building to be consumed by the fire.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] City officials never determined the cause of the blaze, but the rapid spread of the fire due to a long drought in that year's summer, strong winds from the southwest, and the rapid destruction of the water pumping system explain the extensive damage of the mainly wooden city structures.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] There has been much speculation over the years on the single start to the fire.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] The most historically popular tale blames Mrs.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] O'Leary's cow, which allegedly knocked over a lantern; others state that a group of men were gambling inside the barn and knocked over a lantern.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Still other speculation suggests that the blaze was related to other fires in the Midwest that day.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] In 1997, the Chicago City Council formally exonerated O'Leary of any responsibility for the fire, following research by historian Richard Bales.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] The fire's spread was aided by the city's use of wood as the predominant building material in a style called balloon frame.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] More than two-thirds of the structures in Chicago at the time of the fire were made entirely of wood, with most of the houses and buildings being topped with highly combustible tar or shingle roofs.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] All of the city's sidewalks and many roads were also made of wood.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Compounding this problem, Chicago received only 1 inch (25 mm) of rain from July 4 to October 9, causing severe drought conditions before the fire, while strong southwest winds helped to carry flying embers toward the heart of the city.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] In 1871, the Chicago Fire Department had 185 firefighters with just 17 horse-drawn steam pumpers to protect the entire city.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] The initial response by the fire department was timely, but due to an error by the watchman, Mathias Schaffer, the firefighters were initially sent to the wrong place, allowing the fire to grow unchecked.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] An alarm sent from the area near the fire also failed to register at the courthouse where the fire watchmen were, while the firefighters were tired from having fought numerous small fires and one large fire in the week before.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] These factors combined to turn a small barn fire into a conflagration.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] When firefighters finally arrived at DeKoven Street, the fire had grown and spread to neighboring buildings and was progressing toward the central business district.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Firefighters had hoped that the South Branch of the Chicago River and an area that had previously thoroughly burned would act as a natural firebreak.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] All along the river, however, were lumber yards, warehouses, and coal yards, as well as barges, and numerous bridges across the river.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] As the fire grew, the southwest wind intensified and the temperature rose, causing structures to catch fire from the heat and from burning debris blown by the wind.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Around midnight, flaming debris blew across the river and landed on roofs and the South Side Gas Works.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] With the fire across the river and moving rapidly toward the heart of the city, panic set in.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Mason sent messages to nearby towns asking for help.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] When the courthouse caught fire, he ordered the building to be evacuated and the prisoners jailed in the basement to be released.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] At 2:30 a.m. on the 9th, the cupola of the courthouse collapsed, sending the great bell crashing down.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Some witnesses reported hearing the sound from a mile (1.6 km) away.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] As more buildings succumbed to the flames, a major contributing factor to the fire's spread was a meteorological phenomenon known as a fire whirl.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] As hot air rises, it comes into contact with cooler air and begins to spin, creating a tornado-like effect.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] These fire whirls are likely what drove flaming debris so high and so far.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Such debris was blown across the main branch of the Chicago River to a railroad car carrying kerosene.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] The fire had jumped the river a second time and was now raging across the city's north side.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Despite the fire spreading and growing rapidly, the city's firefighters continued to battle the blaze.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] A short time after the fire jumped the river, a burning piece of timber lodged on the roof of the city's waterworks.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Within minutes, the interior of the building was engulfed in flames and the building was destroyed.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] With it, the city's water mains went dry and the city was helpless.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Contemporary Chicago Tribune reporting confirmed that the waterworks roof caught fire at an early hour, forcing firefighters to retreat before the building was lost.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] The fire burned unchecked from building to building, block to block.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] One eyewitness account, reprinted from a Western paper, described a family trapped on the fourth floor of a building at the corner of Randolph and Market Streets, the father throwing his wife and children to safety below before collapsing beside his wife as the flames closed in.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Late in the evening of October 9, it started to rain, but the fire had already started to burn itself out.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] The fire had spread to the sparsely populated areas of the north side, having thoroughly consumed the densely populated areas.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Once the fire had ended, the smoldering remains were still too hot for a survey of the damage to be completed for many days.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Eventually, the city determined that the fire destroyed an area about 4 miles (6 km) long and averaging 3⁄4 mile (1 km) wide, encompassing an area of more than 2,000 acres (809 ha).
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Destroyed were more than 73 miles (117 km) of roads, 120 miles (190 km) of sidewalk, 2,000 lampposts, 17,500 buildings, and $222 million in property, which was about a third of the city's valuation in 1871.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Sheridan's command structure consisted of a mix of regular troops, militia units, police, and a specially organized civilian group "First Regiment of Chicago Volunteers".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Former Lieutenant-Governor William Bross, and part owner of the *Tribune*, later recollected his response to the arrival of Gen.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Sheridan and his soldiers: "Never did deeper emotions of joy overcome me.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Thank God, those most dear to me and the city as well are safe." For two weeks, Sheridan's men patrolled the streets, guarded the relief warehouses, and enforced other regulations.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] On October 24 the troops were relieved of their duties and the volunteers were mustered out of service.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Of the approximately 324,000 inhabitants of Chicago in 1871, 90,000 Chicago residents (about 28% of the population) were left homeless.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] 120 bodies were recovered, but the death toll may have been as high as 300.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] The county coroner speculated that an accurate count was impossible, as some victims may have drowned or had been incinerated, leaving no remains.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] In the days and weeks following the fire, monetary donations flowed into Chicago from around the country and abroad, along with donations of food, clothing, and other goods.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] These donations came from individuals, corporations, and cities.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] New York City gave $450,000 (equivalent to $12.1 million today) along with clothing and provisions, St.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Louis gave $300,000 (equivalent to $8.06 million today), and the Common Council of London gave 1,000 guineas, as well as £7,000 from private donations.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] 40,000) a town meeting raised £518 on the spot.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Cincinnati, Cleveland, and Buffalo, all commercial rivals, donated hundreds and thousands of dollars.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Milwaukee, along with other nearby cities, helped by sending fire-fighting equipment.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Food, clothing and books were brought by train from all over the continent.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Mayor Mason placed the Chicago Relief and Aid Society in charge of the city's relief efforts.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Operating from the First Congregational Church, city officials and aldermen began taking steps to preserve order in Chicago.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Price gouging was a key concern, and in one ordinance, the city set the price of bread at 8¢ for a 12-ounce (340 g) loaf.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Public buildings were opened as places of refuge, and saloons closed at 9 in the evening for the week following the fire.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Many people who were left homeless after the incident were never able to get their normal lives back since all their personal papers and belongings burned in the conflagration.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Tribune reporting also documented deliberate arson during the chaos: one man set fire to the Jesuit Church on the West Side, while a woman was arrested for firing a building on Burnside Street; the man was caught by neighbors, stoned, and beaten to death on the spot.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Burgess of London proposed an "English Book Donation", to spur a free library in Chicago, in their sympathy with Chicago over the damages suffered.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Libraries in Chicago had been private with membership fees.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] In April 1872, the City Council passed the ordinance to establish the free Chicago Public Library, starting with the donation from the United Kingdom of more than 8,000 volumes.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] The fire also led to questions about development in the United States.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Due to Chicago's rapid expansion at that time, the fire led to Americans reflecting on industrialization.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Based on a religious point of view, some said that Americans should return to a more old-fashioned way of life, and that the fire was caused by people ignoring traditional morality.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] On the other hand, others believed that a lesson to be learned from the fire was that cities needed to improve their building techniques.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Olmsted also believed that with brick walls, and disciplined firemen and police, the deaths and damage caused would have been much less.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Almost immediately, the city began to rewrite its fire standards, spurred by the efforts of leading insurance executives, and fire-prevention reformers such as Arthur C.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Chicago soon developed one of the country's leading fire-fighting forces.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Business owners and land speculators such as Gurdon Saltonstall Hubbard quickly set about rebuilding the city.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] The first load of lumber for rebuilding was delivered the day the last burning building was extinguished.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] By the World's Columbian Exposition 22 years later, Chicago hosted more than 21 million visitors.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] The Palmer House hotel burned to the ground in the fire 13 days after its grand opening.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Its developer, Potter Palmer, secured a loan and rebuilt the hotel to higher standards, across the street from the original, proclaiming it to be "The World's First Fireproof Building".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] In 1956, the remaining structures on the original O'Leary property at 558 W.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] DeKoven Street were torn down for construction of the Chicago Fire Academy, a training facility for Chicago firefighters, known as the Quinn Fire Academy or Chicago Fire Department Training Facility.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] A bronze sculpture of stylized flames, entitled *Pillar of Fire* by Egon Weiner, was erected on the point of origin in 1961.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Michael's Church and the Pumping Station were both gutted in the fire, but their exteriors survived, and the buildings were rebuilt using the surviving walls.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Additionally, though the inhabitable portions of the building were destroyed, the bell tower of St.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] James Cathedral survived the fire and was incorporated into the rebuilt church.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] The stones near the top of the tower are still blackened from the soot and smoke.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Almost from the moment the fire broke out, various theories about its cause began to circulate.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] The most popular and enduring legend maintains that the fire began in the O'Leary barn as Mrs.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] The cow kicked over a lantern (or an oil lamp in some versions), setting fire to the barn.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] The O'Leary family denied this, stating that they were in bed before the fire started, but stories of the cow began to spread across the city.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Catherine O'Leary seemed the perfect scapegoat: she was a poor, Irish Catholic immigrant.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] During the latter half of the 19th century, anti-Irish sentiment was strong in Chicago and throughout the United States.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] This was intensified as a result of the growing political power of the city's Irish population.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Furthermore, the United States had been distrustful of Catholics (or papists, as they were often called) since its beginning, carrying over attitudes in England in the 17th century; as an Irish Catholic, Mrs.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] O'Leary was a target of both anti-Catholic and anti-Irish sentiment.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] This story was circulating in Chicago even before the flames had died out, and it was noted in the *Chicago Tribune'*s first post-fire issue.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] In 1893 the reporter Michael Ahern retracted the "cow-and-lantern" story, admitting it was fabricated, but even his confession was unable to put the legend to rest.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Although the O'Learys were never officially charged with starting the fire, the story became so engrained in local lore that Chicago's city council officially exonerated them—and the cow—in 1997.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Amateur historian Richard Bales has suggested the fire started when Daniel "Pegleg" Sullivan, who first reported the fire, ignited hay in the barn while trying to steal milk.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Bales's account does not have consensus.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] The Chicago Public Library staff criticized his account in their web page on the fire.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Despite this, the Chicago city council was convinced of Bales's argument and stated that the actions of Sullivan on that day should be scrutinized after the O'Leary family was exonerated in 1997.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Anthony DeBartolo reported evidence in two articles of the *Chicago Tribune* (October 8, 1997, and March 3, 1998, reprinted in *Hyde Park Media*) suggesting that Louis M.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Cohn may have started the fire during a craps game.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Following his death in 1942, Cohn bequeathed $35,000 which was assigned by his executors to the Medill School of Journalism at Northwestern University.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] The bequest was given to the school on September 28, 1944, and the dedication contained a claim by Cohn to have been present at the start of the fire.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] According to Cohn, on the night of the fire, he was gambling in the O'Learys' barn with one of their sons and some other neighborhood boys.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] O'Leary came out to the barn to chase the gamblers away at around 9:00, they knocked over a lantern in their flight, although Cohn states that he paused long enough to scoop up the money.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] The argument is not universally accepted.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] An alternative theory, first suggested in 1882 by Ignatius L.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Donnelly in *Ragnarok: The Age of Fire and Gravel*, is that the fire was caused by a meteor shower.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] This was described as a "fringe theory" concerning Biela's Comet.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] At a 2004 conference of the Aerospace Corporation and the American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics, engineer and physicist Robert Wood suggested that the fire began when a fragment of Biela's Comet impacted the Midwest.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Biela's Comet had broken apart in 1845 and had not been observed since.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Wood argued that four large fires took place, all on the same day, all on the shores of Lake Michigan (see related events), suggesting a common root cause.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Eyewitnesses reported sighting spontaneous ignitions, lack of smoke, "balls of fire" falling from the sky, and blue flames.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] According to Wood, these accounts suggest that the fires were caused by the methane that is commonly found in comets.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Meteorites are not known to start or spread fires and are cool to the touch after reaching the ground, so this theory has not found favor in the scientific community.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Methane-air mixtures become flammable only when the methane concentration exceeds 5%, at which point the mixtures also become explosive, a situation unlikely to occur from meteorites.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Methane gas is lighter than air and thus does not accumulate near the ground; any localized pockets of methane in the open air rapidly dissipate.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Moreover, if a fragment of an icy comet were to strike the Earth, the most likely outcome, due to the low tensile strength of such bodies, would be for it to disintegrate in the upper atmosphere, leading to a meteor air burst like the Tunguska event.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] The specific choice of Biela's Comet does not match with the dates in question, as the 6-year period of the comet's orbit did not intersect that of the Earth until 1872, one full year after the fire, when a large meteor shower was observed.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] A common cause for the fires in the Midwest in late 1871 is that the area had had a dry summer, so that winds from the front that moved in that evening were capable of generating rapidly expanding blazes from available ignition sources, which were plentiful in the region.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] On that hot, dry, and windy autumn day, three other major fires occurred along the shores of Lake Michigan at the same time as the Great Chicago Fire.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Some 250 miles (400 km) to the north, the Peshtigo Fire consumed the town of Peshtigo, Wisconsin, along with a dozen other villages.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] It killed 1,200 to 2,500 people and charred approximately 1.5 million acres (6,100 km2).
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] The Peshtigo Fire remains the deadliest in American history but the remoteness of the region meant it was little noticed at the time, because one of the first things that burned were the telegraph lines to Green Bay.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Across the lake to the east, the town of Holland, Michigan, and other nearby areas burned to the ground.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Some 100 miles (160 km) to the north of Holland, the lumbering community of Manistee also went up in flames in what became known as the Great Michigan Fire.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Farther east, along the shore of Lake Huron, the Port Huron Fire swept through Port Huron, Michigan and much of Michigan's "Thumb".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] On October 9, 1871, a fire swept through the city of Urbana, Illinois, 140 miles (230 km) south of Chicago, destroying portions of its downtown area.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] Windsor, Ontario, likewise burned on October 12.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] The town of Singapore, Michigan, provided a large portion of the lumber to rebuild Chicago.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/great-chicago-fire] As a result, Singapore was so heavily deforested that the land deteriorated into barren sand dunes that buried the town, which had to be abandoned.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Longfellow was born in Portland, District of Maine, Massachusetts (now Portland, Maine).
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He graduated from Bowdoin College and became a professor there and, later, at Harvard College after studying in Europe.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] His first major poetry collections were *Voices of the Night* (1839) and *Ballads and Other Poems* (1841).
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He retired from teaching in 1854 to focus on his writing, and he lived the remainder of his life in the Revolutionary War headquarters of George Washington in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Longfellow's first wife, Mary Potter, died in 1835 after a miscarriage.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] His second wife, Frances Appleton, died in 1861 after sustaining burns when her dress caught fire.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] After her death, he had difficulty writing poetry for a time and focused on translating works from foreign languages.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Longfellow wrote many lyric poems known for their musicality and often presenting stories of mythology and legend.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He became the most popular American poet of his day and had success overseas.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He has been criticized for imitating European styles and writing poetry that was too sentimental.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Longfellow was born on February 27, 1807, to Stephen Longfellow and Zilpah (Wadsworth) Longfellow in Portland, Maine, then a district of Massachusetts.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Although he was born at the now-demolished 159–161 Fore Street, he grew up in what is now known as the Wadsworth-Longfellow House on Congress Street.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] His father was a lawyer, and his maternal grandfather was Peleg Wadsworth, a general in the American Revolutionary War and a Member of Congress.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] His mother was descended from Richard Warren, a passenger on the *Mayflower*.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He was named after his mother's brother Henry Wadsworth, a Navy lieutenant who had died three years earlier at the Battle of Tripoli.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Longfellow was descended from English colonists who settled in New England in the early 1600s.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] They included *Mayflower* Pilgrims Richard Warren, William Brewster, and John and Priscilla Alden through their daughter Elizabeth Pabodie, the first child born in Plymouth Colony.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Longfellow attended a dame school at the age of three and was enrolled by age six at the private Portland Academy.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] In his years there, he earned a reputation as being very studious and became fluent in Latin.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] His mother encouraged his enthusiasm for reading and learning, introducing him to *Robinson Crusoe* and *Don Quixote*.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He published his first poem at age 13 in the Portland *Gazette* on November 17, 1820, a patriotic and historical four-stanza poem called "The Battle of Lovell's Pond".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He studied at the Portland Academy until age 14.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He spent much of his summers as a child at his grandfather Peleg's farm in Hiram, Maine.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] In the fall of 1822, 15-year-old Longfellow enrolled at Bowdoin College in Brunswick, Maine, along with his brother Stephen.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] His grandfather was a founder of the college and his father was a trustee.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] There Longfellow met Nathaniel Hawthorne who became his lifelong friend.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He boarded with a clergyman for a time before rooming on the third floor in 1823 of what is now known as Winthrop Hall.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He joined the Peucinian Society, a group of students with Federalist leanings.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He pursued his literary goals by submitting poetry and prose to various newspapers and magazines, partly due to encouragement from Professor Thomas Cogswell Upham.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He published nearly 40 minor poems between January 1824 and his graduation in 1825.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] About 24 of them were published in the short-lived Boston periodical *The United States Literary Gazette*.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] When Longfellow graduated from Bowdoin, he was ranked fourth in the class and had been elected to Phi Beta Kappa.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He gave the student commencement address.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] After graduating in 1825, Longfellow was offered a job as professor of modern languages at his alma mater.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] An apocryphal story claims that college trustee Benjamin Orr had been impressed by Longfellow's translation of Horace and hired him under the condition that he travel to Europe to study French, Spanish, and Italian.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Whatever the catalyst, Longfellow began his tour of Europe in May 1826 aboard the ship *Cadmus*.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] His time abroad lasted three years and cost his father $2,604.24, the equivalent of over $67,000 today.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He traveled to France, Spain, Italy, Germany, back to France, then to England before returning to the United States in mid-August 1829.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] While overseas, he learned French, Italian, Spanish, Portuguese, and German, mostly without formal instruction.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] In Madrid, he spent time with Washington Irving and was particularly impressed by the author's work ethic.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Irving encouraged the young Longfellow to pursue writing.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] While in Spain, Longfellow was saddened to learn that his favorite sister Elizabeth had died of tuberculosis at the age of 20 in May 1829.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] On August 27, 1829, he wrote to the president of Bowdoin that he was turning down the professorship because he considered the $600 (~$18,141 in 2025) salary "disproportionate to the duties required".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] The trustees raised his salary to $800 with an additional $100 to serve as the college's librarian, a post which required one hour of work per day.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] During his years teaching at the college, he translated textbooks from French, Italian, and Spanish; his first published book was a translation of the poetry of medieval Spanish poet Jorge Manrique in 1833.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He published the travel book *Outre-Mer: A Pilgrimage Beyond the Sea* in serial form before a book edition was released in 1835.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Shortly after the book's publication, Longfellow attempted to join the literary circle in New York and asked George Pope Morris for an editorial role at one of Morris's publications.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He considered moving to New York after New York University proposed offering him a newly created professorship of modern languages, but there would be no salary.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] The professorship was not created and Longfellow agreed to continue teaching at Bowdoin.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He wrote, "I hate the sight of pen, ink, and paper ...
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] I do not believe that I was born for such a lot.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] On September 14, 1831, Longfellow married Mary Storer Potter, a childhood friend from Portland.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] The couple settled in Brunswick, but the two were not happy there.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Longfellow published several nonfiction and fiction prose pieces in 1833 inspired by Irving, including "The Indian Summer" and "The Bald Eagle".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] In December 1834, Longfellow received a letter from Josiah Quincy III, president of Harvard College, offering him the Smith Professorship of Modern Languages with the stipulation that he spend a year or so abroad.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] There, he further studied German as well as Dutch, Danish, Swedish, Finnish, and Icelandic.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] In October 1835, his wife Mary had a miscarriage during the trip, about six months into her pregnancy.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] She did not recover and died after several weeks of illness at the age of 22 on November 29, 1835.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Longfellow had her body embalmed immediately and placed in a lead coffin inside an oak coffin, which was shipped to Mount Auburn Cemetery near Boston.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He was deeply saddened by her death and wrote: "One thought occupies me night and day...She is dead – She is dead!
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Three years later, he was inspired to write the poem "Footsteps of Angels" about her.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Several years later, he wrote the poem "Mezzo Cammin", which expressed his personal struggles in his middle years.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Longfellow returned to the United States in 1836 and took up the professorship at Harvard.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He was required to live in Cambridge to be close to the campus and, therefore, rented rooms at the Craigie House in the spring of 1837.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] The home was built in 1759 and was the headquarters of George Washington during the Siege of Boston beginning in July 1775.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Elizabeth Craigie owned the home, the widow of Andrew Craigie, and she rented rooms on the second floor.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Previous boarders included Jared Sparks, Edward Everett, and Joseph Emerson Worcester.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] It is preserved today as the Longfellow House–Washington's Headquarters National Historic Site.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Longfellow began publishing his poetry in 1839, including the collection *Voices of the Night*, his debut book of poetry.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] The bulk of *Voices of the Night* was translations, but he included nine original poems and seven poems that he had written as a teenager.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] *Ballads and Other Poems* was published in 1841 and included "The Village Blacksmith" and "The Wreck of the Hesperus", which were instantly popular.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He became part of the local social scene, creating a group of friends who called themselves the Five of Clubs.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Members included Cornelius Conway Felton, George Stillman Hillard, and Charles Sumner; Sumner became Longfellow's closest friend over the next 30 years.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Longfellow met Boston industrialist Nathan Appleton and his son Thomas Gold Appleton in the town of Thun, Switzerland.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] There he began courting Appleton's daughter Frances "Fanny" Appleton.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] The independent-minded Fanny was not interested in marriage, but Longfellow was determined.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] In July 1839, he wrote to a friend: "Victory hangs doubtful.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] It is not *pride*, but the madness of passion".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] His friend George Stillman Hillard encouraged him in the pursuit: "I delight to see you keeping up so stout a heart for the resolve to conquer is half the battle in love as well as war".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] During the courtship, Longfellow frequently walked from Cambridge to the Appleton home in Beacon Hill in Boston by crossing the Boston Bridge.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] That bridge was replaced in 1906 by a new bridge which was later renamed the Longfellow Bridge.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] In late 1839, Longfellow published *Hyperion*, inspired by his trips abroad and his unsuccessful courtship of Fanny Appleton.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Amidst this, he fell into "periods of neurotic depression with moments of panic" and took a six-month leave of absence from Harvard University to attend a health spa in the former Marienberg Benedictine Convent at Boppard in Germany.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] After returning, he published the play *The Spanish Student* in 1842, reflecting his memories from his time in Spain in the 1820s.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] The small collection *Poems on Slavery* was published in 1842 as Longfellow's first public support of abolitionism.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] However, as Longfellow himself wrote, the poems were "so mild that even a Slaveholder might read them without losing his appetite for breakfast".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] A critic for *The Dial* agreed, calling it "the thinnest of all Mr.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Longfellow's thin books; spirited and polished like its forerunners; but the topic would warrant a deeper tone".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] The New England Anti-Slavery Society, however, was satisfied enough with the collection to reprint it for further distribution.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] On May 10, 1843, Longfellow received a letter from Fanny Appleton agreeing to marry him.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He was too restless to take a carriage and walked 90 minutes to meet her at her house.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] They were soon married; Nathan Appleton bought the Craigie House as a wedding present, and Longfellow lived there for the rest of his life.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] His love for Fanny is evident in the following lines from his only love poem, the sonnet "The Evening Star" which he wrote in October 1845: "O my beloved, my sweet Hesperus!
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Their second-youngest daughter was Edith, who married Richard Henry Dana III, son of Richard Henry Dana Jr. who wrote *Two Years Before the Mast*.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Their daughter Fanny was born on April 7, 1847, and Dr.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Nathan Cooley Keep administered ether to the mother as the first obstetric anesthetic in the United States.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Longfellow published his epic poem *Evangeline* for the first time a few months later on November 1, 1847.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] His literary income was increasing considerably; in 1840, he had made $219 from his work, but 1850 brought him $1,900.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] On June 14, 1853, Longfellow held a farewell dinner party at his Cambridge home for his friend Nathaniel Hawthorne, who was preparing to move overseas.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] In 1854, he retired from Harvard, devoting himself entirely to writing.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He was awarded an honorary doctorate of laws from Harvard in 1859.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Frances was putting locks of her children's hair into an envelope on July 9, 1861 and attempting to seal it with hot sealing wax while Longfellow took a nap.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Her dress suddenly caught fire, but it is unclear exactly how; burning wax or a lighted candle may have fallen onto it.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Longfellow was awakened from his nap and rushed to help her, throwing a rug over her, but it was too small.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He stifled the flames with his body, but she was badly burned.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Longfellow's youngest daughter Annie explained the story differently some 50 years later, claiming that there had been no candle or wax but that the fire had started from a self-lighting match that had fallen on the floor.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Both accounts state that Frances was taken to her room to recover, and a doctor was called.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] She was in and out of consciousness throughout the night and was administered ether.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] She died shortly after 10 the next morning, July 10, after requesting a cup of coffee.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Longfellow had burned himself while trying to save her, badly enough that he was unable to attend her funeral.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] His facial injuries led him to stop shaving, and he wore a beard from then on which became his trademark.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Longfellow was devastated by Frances's death and never fully recovered; he occasionally resorted to laudanum and ether to deal with his grief.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He worried that he would go insane, begging "not to be sent to an asylum" and noting that he was "inwardly bleeding to death".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] And seasons, changeless since the day she died.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Longfellow spent several years translating Dante Alighieri's *Divine Comedy*.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] To aid him in perfecting the translation and reviewing proofs, he invited friends to meetings every Wednesday starting in 1864.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] The "Dante Club", as it was called, regularly included William Dean Howells, James Russell Lowell, and Charles Eliot Norton, as well as other occasional guests.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] The full three-volume translation was published in the spring of 1867, but Longfellow continued to revise it.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] It went through four printings in its first year.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] In 1874, Samuel Ward helped him sell the poem "The Hanging of the Crane" to *The New York Ledger* for $3,000 (~$85,368 in 2025).
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] At that time, this was the highest price ever paid for a poem.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Longfellow supported abolitionism and especially hoped for reconciliation between the northern and southern states after the American Civil War.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] His son Charles was injured during the war, and he wrote the poem "Christmas Bells", later the basis of the carol *I Heard the Bells on Christmas Day*.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He wrote in his journal in 1878: "I have only one desire; and that is for harmony, and a frank and honest understanding between North and South".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Longfellow accepted an offer from Joshua Chamberlain to speak at his fiftieth reunion at Bowdoin College, despite his aversion to public speaking.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He read the poem "Morituri Salutamus" so quietly that few could hear him.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] The next year, he declined an offer to be nominated for the Board of Overseers at Harvard "for reasons very conclusive to my own mind".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] On August 22, 1879, a female admirer traveled to Longfellow's house in Cambridge and, unaware to whom she was speaking, asked him: "Is this the house where Longfellow was born?" He told her that it was not.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] The visitor then asked if he had died here.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] In March 1882, Longfellow went to bed with severe stomach pain.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He endured the pain for several days with the help of opium before he died surrounded by family on Friday, March 24.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] At the time of his death, his estate was worth an estimated $356,320 (~$12.3 million in 2024 terms).
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] He is buried with both of his wives at Mount Auburn Cemetery in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] His last few years were spent translating the poetry of Michelangelo.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Longfellow never considered it complete enough to be published during his lifetime, but a posthumous edition was collected in 1883.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Scholars generally regard the work as autobiographical, reflecting the translator as an aging artist facing his impending death.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Much of Longfellow's work is categorized as lyric poetry, but he experimented with many forms, including hexameter and free verse.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] His published poetry shows great versatility, using anapestic and trochaic forms, blank verse, heroic couplets, ballads, and sonnets.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Typically, he would carefully consider the subject of his poetic ideas for a long time before deciding on the right metrical form for it.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Much of his work is recognized for its melodious musicality.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] As he says, "what a writer asks of his reader is not so much to *like* as to *listen*".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] As a very private man, Longfellow did not often add autobiographical elements to his poetry.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Two notable exceptions are dedicated to the death of members of his family.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] "Resignation" was written as a response to the death of his daughter Fanny in 1848; it does not use first-person pronouns and is instead a generalized poem of mourning.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] The death of his second wife Frances, as biographer Charles Calhoun wrote, deeply affected Longfellow personally but "seemed not to touch his poetry, at least directly".
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] His memorial poem to her was the sonnet "The Cross of Snow" and was not published in his lifetime.
[src:1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine/henry-wadsworth-longfellow] Longfellow often used didacticism in his poetry, but he focused on it less in his later years.
